# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: geophysics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The magnitude of Earth's magnetic field at its surface ranges from 25,000 to 65,000 nT (0.25 to 0.65 G).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] As an approximation, it is represented by a field of a magnetic dipole currently tilted at an angle of about 11° with respect to Earth's rotational axis, as if there were an enormous bar magnet placed at that angle through the center of Earth.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] While the North and South magnetic poles are usually located near the geographic poles, they slowly and continuously move over geological time scales, but sufficiently slowly for ordinary compasses to remain useful for navigation.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] However, at irregular intervals averaging several hundred thousand years, Earth's field reverses and the North and South Magnetic Poles abruptly switch places.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] These reversals of the geomagnetic poles leave a record in rocks that are of value to paleomagnetists in calculating geomagnetic fields in the past.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Such information in turn is helpful in studying the motions of continents and ocean floors.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The magnetosphere is defined by the extent of Earth's magnetic field in space or geospace.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] It extends above the ionosphere, several tens of thousands of kilometres into space, protecting Earth from the charged particles of the solar wind and cosmic rays that would otherwise strip away the upper atmosphere, including the ozone layer that protects Earth from harmful ultraviolet radiation.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Earth's magnetic field deflects most of the solar wind, whose charged particles would otherwise strip away the ozone layer that protects the Earth from harmful ultraviolet radiation.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] One stripping mechanism is for gas to be caught in bubbles of the magnetic field, which are ripped off by solar winds.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Calculations of the loss of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere of Mars, resulting from scavenging of ions by the solar wind, indicate that the dissipation of the magnetic field of Mars caused a near total loss of its atmosphere.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The study of the past magnetic field of the Earth is known as paleomagnetism.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Reversals also provide the basis for magnetostratigraphy, a way of dating rocks and sediments.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The field also magnetizes the crust, and magnetic anomalies can be used to search for deposits of metal ores.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Humans have used compasses for direction finding since the 11th century A.D. and for navigation since the 12th century.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Although the magnetic declination does shift with time, this wandering is slow enough that a simple compass can remain useful for navigation.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Using magnetoreception, various other organisms, ranging from some types of bacteria to pigeons, use the Earth's magnetic field for orientation and navigation.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] At any location, the Earth's magnetic field can be represented by a three-dimensional vector.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A typical procedure for measuring its direction is to use a compass to determine the direction of magnetic North.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Its angle relative to true North is the *declination* (*D*) or *variation*.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Facing magnetic North, the angle the field makes with the horizontal is the *inclination* (*I*) or *magnetic dip*.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The *intensity* (*F*) of the field is proportional to the force it exerts on a magnet.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Another common representation is in *X* (North), *Y* (East) and *Z* (Down) coordinates.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The Earth's field ranges between approximately 22 and 67 μT (0.22 and 0.67 G).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] By comparison, a strong refrigerator magnet has a field of about 10,000 μT (100 G).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The intensity of the field is more correctly called "flux density"; the SI unit is a tesla (T) but a gauss (G), may also be used, with 1 G = 100 μT.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A map of intensity contours is called an *isodynamic chart*.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] As the World Magnetic Model shows, the intensity tends to decrease from the poles to the equator.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A minimum intensity occurs in the South Atlantic Anomaly over South America while there are maxima over northern Canada, Siberia, and the coast of Antarctica south of Australia.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The intensity of the magnetic field is subject to change over time.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A 2021 paleomagnetic study from the University of Liverpool contributed to a growing body of evidence that the Earth's magnetic field cycles with intensity every 200 million years.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The inclination is given by an angle that can assume values between −90° (up) to 90° (down).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] In the northern hemisphere, the field points downwards.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] It is straight down at the North Magnetic Pole and rotates upwards as the latitude decreases until it is horizontal (0°) at the magnetic equator.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] It continues to rotate upwards until it is straight up at the South Magnetic Pole.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Inclination can be measured with a dip circle.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] An *isoclinic chart* (map of inclination contours) for the Earth's magnetic field is shown below.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Declination is positive for an eastward deviation of the field relative to true north.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] It can be estimated by comparing the magnetic north–south heading on a compass with the direction of a celestial pole.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Maps typically include information on the declination as an angle or a small diagram showing the relationship between magnetic north and true north.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Information on declination for a region can be represented by a chart with isogonic lines (contour lines with each line representing a fixed declination).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Components of the Earth's magnetic field at the surface from the World Magnetic Model for 2020.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Near the surface of the Earth, its magnetic field can be closely approximated by the field of a magnetic dipole positioned at the center of the Earth and tilted at an angle of about 11° with respect to the rotational axis of the Earth.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The dipole is roughly equivalent to a powerful bar magnet, with its south pole pointing towards the geomagnetic North Pole.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This may seem surprising, but the north pole of a magnet is so defined because, if allowed to rotate freely, it points roughly northward (in the geographic sense).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Since the north pole of a magnet attracts the south poles of other magnets and repels the north poles, it must be attracted to the south pole of Earth's magnet.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The dipolar field accounts for 80–90% of the field in most locations.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Historically, the north and south poles of a magnet were first defined by the Earth's magnetic field, not vice versa, since one of the first uses for a magnet was as a compass needle.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A magnet's North pole is defined as the pole that is attracted by the Earth's North Magnetic Pole, in the arctic region, when the magnet is suspended so it can turn freely.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Since opposite poles attract, the North Magnetic Pole of the Earth is really the south pole of its magnetic field (the place where the field is directed downward into the Earth).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The positions of the magnetic poles can be defined in at least two ways: locally or globally.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The local definition is the point where the magnetic field is vertical.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This can be determined by measuring the inclination.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The inclination of the Earth's field is 90° (downwards) at the North Magnetic Pole and –90° (upwards) at the South Magnetic Pole.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The two poles wander independently of each other and are not directly opposite each other on the globe.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Movements of up to 40 kilometres (25 mi) per year have been observed for the North Magnetic Pole.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Over the last 180 years, the North Magnetic Pole has been migrating northwestward, from Cape Adelaide in the Boothia Peninsula in 1831 to 600 kilometres (370 mi) from Resolute Bay in 2001.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The *magnetic equator* is the line where the inclination is zero (the magnetic field is horizontal).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The global definition of the Earth's field is based on a mathematical model.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] If a line is drawn through the center of the Earth, parallel to the moment of the best-fitting magnetic dipole, the two positions where it intersects the Earth's surface are called the North and South geomagnetic poles.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] If the Earth's magnetic field were perfectly dipolar, the geomagnetic poles and magnetic dip poles would coincide and compasses would point towards them.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] However, the Earth's field has a significant non-dipolar contribution, so the poles do not coincide and compasses do not generally point at either.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Earth's magnetic field, predominantly dipolar at its surface, is distorted further out by the solar wind.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This is a stream of charged particles leaving the Sun's corona and accelerating to a speed of 200 to 1000 kilometres per second.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] They carry with them a magnetic field, the interplanetary magnetic field (IMF).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The solar wind exerts a pressure, and if it could reach Earth's atmosphere it would erode it.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] However, it is kept away by the pressure of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The magnetopause, the area where the pressures balance, is the boundary of the magnetosphere.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Despite its name, the magnetosphere is asymmetric, with the sunward side being about 10 Earth radii out but with the other side stretching out in a magnetotail that extends beyond 200 Earth radii.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Sunward of the magnetopause is the bow shock, the area where the solar wind slows abruptly.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Inside the magnetosphere is the plasmasphere, a donut-shaped region containing low-energy charged particles, or plasma.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This region begins at a height of 60 km, extends up to 3 or 4 Earth radii, and includes the ionosphere.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] There are also two concentric tire-shaped regions, called the Van Allen radiation belts, with high-energy ions (energies from 0.1 to 10 MeV).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The inner belt is 1–2 Earth radii out while the outer belt is at 4–7 Earth radii.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The plasmasphere and Van Allen belts have partial overlap, with the extent of overlap varying greatly with solar activity.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] As well as deflecting the solar wind, the Earth's magnetic field deflects cosmic rays, high-energy charged particles that are mostly from outside the Solar System.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Many cosmic rays are kept out of the Solar System by the Sun's magnetosphere, or heliosphere.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] By contrast, astronauts on the Moon risk exposure to radiation.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Anyone who had been on the Moon's surface during a particularly violent solar eruption in 2005 would have received a lethal dose.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Some of the charged particles do get into the magnetosphere.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] These spiral around field lines, bouncing back and forth between the poles several times per second.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] In addition, positive ions slowly drift westward and negative ions drift eastward, giving rise to a ring current.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This current reduces the magnetic field at the Earth's surface.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Particles that penetrate the ionosphere and collide with the atoms there give rise to the lights of the aurorae while also emitting X-rays.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The varying conditions in the magnetosphere, known as space weather, are largely driven by solar activity.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] If the solar wind is weak, the magnetosphere expands; while if it is strong, it compresses the magnetosphere and more of it gets in.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Periods of particularly intense activity, called geomagnetic storms, can occur when a coronal mass ejection erupts above the Sun and sends a shock wave through the Solar System.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Such a wave can take just two days to reach the Earth.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Geomagnetic storms can cause a lot of disruption; the "Halloween" storm of 2003 damaged more than a third of NASA's satellites.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The largest documented storm, the Carrington Event, occurred in 1859.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] It induced currents strong enough to disrupt telegraph lines, and aurorae were reported as far south as Hawaii.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The geomagnetic field changes on time scales from milliseconds to millions of years.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Shorter time scales mostly arise from currents in the ionosphere (ionospheric dynamo region) and magnetosphere, and some changes can be traced to geomagnetic storms or daily variations in currents.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Changes over time scales of a year or more mostly reflect changes in the Earth's interior, particularly the iron-rich core.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Frequently, the Earth's magnetosphere is hit by solar flares causing geomagnetic storms, provoking displays of aurorae.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The short-term instability of the magnetic field is measured with the K-index.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Data from THEMIS show that the magnetic field, which interacts with the solar wind, is reduced when the magnetic orientation is aligned between Sun and Earth – opposite to the previous hypothesis.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] During forthcoming solar storms, this could result in blackouts and disruptions in artificial satellites.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Changes in Earth's magnetic field on a time scale of a year or more are referred to as *secular variation*.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Over hundreds of years, magnetic declination is observed to vary over tens of degrees.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The animation shows how global declinations have changed over the last few centuries.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The direction and intensity of the dipole change over time.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Over the last two centuries the dipole strength has been decreasing at a rate of about 6.3% per century.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] At this rate of decrease, the field would be negligible in about 1600 years.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] However, this strength is about average for the last 7 thousand years, and the current rate of change is not unusual.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A prominent feature in the non-dipolar part of the secular variation is a *westward drift* at a rate of about 0.2° per year.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This drift is not the same everywhere and has varied over time.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The globally averaged drift has been westward since about 1400 AD but eastward between about 1000 AD and 1400 AD.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Changes that predate magnetic observatories are recorded in archaeological and geological materials.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Such changes are referred to as *paleomagnetic secular variation* or *paleosecular variation (PSV)*.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The records typically include long periods of small change with occasional large changes reflecting geomagnetic excursions and reversals.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A 1995 study of lava flows on Steens Mountain, Oregon appeared to suggest the magnetic field once shifted at a rate of up to 6° per day at some time in Earth's history, a surprising result.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] However, in 2014 one of the original authors published a new study which found the results were actually due to the continuous thermal demagnetization of the lava, not to a shift in the magnetic field.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] In July 2020 scientists report that analysis of simulations and a recent observational field model show that maximum rates of directional change of Earth's magnetic field reached ~10° per year – almost 100 times faster than current changes and 10 times faster than previously thought.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Although generally Earth's field is approximately dipolar, with an axis that is nearly aligned with the rotational axis, occasionally the North and South geomagnetic poles trade places.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Evidence for these *geomagnetic reversals* can be found in basalts, sediment cores taken from the ocean floors, and seafloor magnetic anomalies.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Reversals occur nearly randomly in time, with intervals between reversals ranging from less than 0.1 million years to as much as 50 million years.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The most recent geomagnetic reversal, called the Brunhes–Matuyama reversal, occurred about 780,000 years ago.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A related phenomenon, a geomagnetic *excursion*, takes the dipole axis across the equator and then back to the original polarity.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The Laschamp event is an example of an excursion, occurring during the last ice age (41,000 years ago).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The past magnetic field is recorded mostly by strongly magnetic minerals, particularly iron oxides such as magnetite, that can carry a permanent magnetic moment.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This remanent magnetization, or *remanence*, can be acquired in more than one way.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] In lava flows, the direction of the field is "frozen" in small minerals as they cool, giving rise to a thermoremanent magnetization.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] In sediments, the orientation of magnetic particles acquires a slight bias towards the magnetic field as they are deposited on an ocean floor or lake bottom.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This is called *detrital remanent magnetization*.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Thermoremanent magnetization is the main source of the magnetic anomalies around mid-ocean ridges.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] As the seafloor spreads, magma wells up from the mantle, cools to form new basaltic crust on both sides of the ridge, and is carried away from it by seafloor spreading.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] As it cools, it records the direction of the Earth's field.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] When the Earth's field reverses, new basalt records the reversed direction.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The result is a series of stripes that are symmetric about the ridge.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A ship towing a magnetometer on the surface of the ocean can detect these stripes and infer the age of the ocean floor below.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This provides information on the rate at which seafloor has spread in the past.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Radiometric dating of lava flows has been used to establish a *geomagnetic polarity time scale*, part of which is shown in the image.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This forms the basis of magnetostratigraphy, a geophysical correlation technique that can be used to date both sedimentary and volcanic sequences as well as the seafloor magnetic anomalies.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Paleomagnetic studies of Paleoarchean lava in Australia and conglomerate in South Africa have concluded that the magnetic field has been present since at least about 3,450 million years ago.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] In 2024 researchers published evidence from Greenland for the existence of the magnetic field as early as 3,700 million years ago.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The rate of decrease and the current strength are within the normal range of variation, as shown by the record of past magnetic fields recorded in rocks.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The nature of Earth's magnetic field is one of heteroscedastic (seemingly random) fluctuation.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] An instantaneous measurement of it, or several measurements of it across the span of decades or centuries, are not sufficient to extrapolate an overall trend in the field strength.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] It has gone up and down in the past for unknown reasons.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Also, noting the local intensity of the dipole field (or its fluctuation) is insufficient to characterize Earth's magnetic field as a whole, as it is not strictly a dipole field.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The dipole component of Earth's field can diminish even while the total magnetic field remains the same or increases.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The Earth's magnetic north pole is drifting from northern Canada towards Siberia with a presently accelerating rate—10 kilometres (6.2 mi) per year at the beginning of the 1900s, up to 40 kilometres (25 mi) per year in 2003, and since then has only accelerated.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The Earth's magnetic field is believed to be generated by electric currents in the conductive iron alloys of its core, created by convection currents due to heat escaping from the core.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The Earth and most of the planets in the Solar System, as well as the Sun and other stars, all generate magnetic fields through the motion of electrically conducting fluids.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The Earth's field originates in its core.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This is a region of iron alloys extending to about 3400 km (the radius of the Earth is 6370 km).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] It is divided into a solid inner core, with a radius of 1220 km, and a liquid outer core.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The motion of the liquid in the outer core is driven by heat flow from the inner core, which is about 6,000 K (5,730 °C; 10,340 °F), to the core-mantle boundary, which is about 3,800 K (3,530 °C; 6,380 °F).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The heat is generated by potential energy released by heavier materials sinking toward the core (planetary differentiation, the iron catastrophe) as well as decay of radioactive elements in the interior.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The pattern of flow is organized by the rotation of the Earth and the presence of the solid inner core.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The mechanism by which the Earth generates a magnetic field is known as a geodynamo.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] where **u** is the velocity of the fluid; **B** is the magnetic B-field; and *η* = 1/*σμ* is the magnetic diffusivity, which is the reciprocal of the product of the electrical conductivity σ and the permeability μ .
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The term ∂**B**/∂*t* is the partial derivative of the field with respect to time; ∇2 is the Laplace operator, ∇× is the curl operator, and × is the vector product.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The first term on the right hand side of the induction equation is a diffusion term.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] In a stationary fluid, the magnetic field declines and any concentrations of field spread out.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] If the Earth's dynamo shut off, the dipole part would disappear in a few tens of thousands of years.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] In a perfect conductor ( $\sigma =\infty \;$ ), there would be no diffusion.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] By Lenz's law, any change in the magnetic field would be immediately opposed by currents, so the flux through a given volume of fluid could not change.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] As the fluid moved, the magnetic field would go with it.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The theorem describing this effect is called the *frozen-in-field theorem*.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Even in a fluid with a finite conductivity, new field is generated by stretching field lines as the fluid moves in ways that deform it.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This process could go on generating new field indefinitely, were it not that as the magnetic field increases in strength, it resists fluid motion.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The motion of the fluid is sustained by convection, motion driven by buoyancy.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The temperature increases towards the center of the Earth, and the higher temperature of the fluid lower down makes it buoyant.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This buoyancy is enhanced by chemical separation: As the core cools, some of the molten iron solidifies and is plated to the inner core.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] In the process, lighter elements are left behind in the fluid, making it lighter.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This is called *compositional convection*.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A Coriolis effect, caused by the overall planetary rotation, tends to organize the flow into rolls aligned along the north–south polar axis.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A dynamo can amplify a magnetic field, but it needs a "seed" field to get it started.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] For the Earth, this could have been an external magnetic field.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Early in its history the Sun went through a T-Tauri phase in which the solar wind would have had a magnetic field orders of magnitude larger than the present solar wind.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] However, much of the field may have been screened out by the Earth's mantle.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] An alternative source is currents in the core-mantle boundary driven by chemical reactions or variations in thermal or electric conductivity.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Such effects may still provide a small bias that are part of the boundary conditions for the geodynamo.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The average magnetic field in the Earth's outer core was calculated to be 25 gauss, 50 times stronger than the field at the surface.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Simulating the geodynamo by computer requires numerically solving a set of nonlinear partial differential equations for the magnetohydrodynamics (MHD) of the Earth's interior.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Simulation of the MHD equations is performed on a 3D grid of points and the fineness of the grid, which in part determines the realism of the solutions, is limited mainly by computer power.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] For decades, theorists were confined to creating *kinematic dynamo* computer models in which the fluid motion is chosen in advance and the effect on the magnetic field calculated.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Kinematic dynamo theory was mainly a matter of trying different flow geometries and testing whether such geometries could sustain a dynamo.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The first *self-consistent* dynamo models, ones that determine both the fluid motions and the magnetic field, were developed by two groups in 1995, one in Japan and one in the United States.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The latter received attention because it successfully reproduced some of the characteristics of the Earth's field, including geomagnetic reversals.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The oceans contribute to Earth's magnetic field.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Seawater is an electrical conductor, and therefore interacts with the magnetic field.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] As the tides cycle around the ocean basins, the ocean water essentially tries to pull the geomagnetic field lines along.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Because the salty water is only slightly conductive, the interaction is relatively weak: the strongest component is from the regular lunar tide that happens about twice per day (M2).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Other contributions come from ocean swell, eddies, and even tsunamis.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The strength of the interaction depends also on the temperature of the ocean water.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The entire heat stored in the ocean can now be inferred from observations of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Electric currents induced in the ionosphere generate magnetic fields (ionospheric dynamo region).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Such a field is always generated near where the atmosphere is closest to the Sun, causing daily alterations that can deflect surface magnetic fields by as much as 1°.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Typical daily variations of field strength are about 25 nT (one part in 2000), with variations over a few seconds of typically around 1 nT (one part in 50,000).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The Earth's magnetic field strength was measured by Carl Friedrich Gauss in 1832 and has been repeatedly measured since then, showing a relative decay of about 10% over the last 150 years.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The Magsat satellite and later satellites have used 3-axis vector magnetometers to probe the 3-D structure of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The later Ørsted satellite allowed a comparison indicating a dynamic geodynamo in action that appears to be giving rise to an alternate pole under the Atlantic Ocean west of South Africa.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Governments sometimes operate units that specialize in measurement of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] These are geomagnetic observatories, typically part of a national Geological survey, for example, the British Geological Survey's Eskdalemuir Observatory.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Such observatories can measure and forecast magnetic conditions such as magnetic storms that sometimes affect communications, electric power, and other human activities.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The International Real-time Magnetic Observatory Network, with over 100 interlinked geomagnetic observatories around the world, has been recording the Earth's magnetic field since 1991.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The military determines local geomagnetic field characteristics, in order to detect *anomalies* in the natural background that might be caused by a significant metallic object such as a submerged submarine.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Typically, these magnetic anomaly detectors are flown in aircraft like the UK's Nimrod or towed as an instrument or an array of instruments from surface ships.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Commercially, geophysical prospecting companies also use magnetic detectors to identify naturally occurring anomalies from ore bodies, such as the Kursk Magnetic Anomaly.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Magnetometers detect minute deviations in the Earth's magnetic field caused by iron artifacts, kilns, some types of stone structures, and even ditches and middens in archaeological geophysics.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Using magnetic instruments adapted from airborne magnetic anomaly detectors developed during World War II to detect submarines, the magnetic variations across the ocean floor have been mapped.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Basalt — the iron-rich, volcanic rock making up the ocean floor — contains a strongly magnetic mineral (magnetite) and can locally distort compass readings.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The distortion was recognized by Icelandic mariners as early as the late 18th century.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] More important, because the presence of magnetite gives the basalt measurable magnetic properties, these magnetic variations have provided another means to study the deep ocean floor.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] When newly formed rock cools, such magnetic materials record the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Each measurement of the magnetic field is at a particular place and time.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] If an accurate estimate of the field at some other place and time is needed, the measurements must be converted to a model and the model used to make predictions.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The most common way of analyzing the global variations in the Earth's magnetic field is to fit the measurements to a set of spherical harmonics.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This was first done by Carl Friedrich Gauss.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Spherical harmonics are functions that oscillate over the surface of a sphere.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] They are the product of two functions, one that depends on latitude and one on longitude.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The function of longitude is zero along zero or more great circles passing through the North and South Poles; the number of such *nodal lines* is the absolute value of the *order* *m*.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The function of latitude is zero along zero or more latitude circles; this plus the order is equal to the *degree* ℓ.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Each harmonic is equivalent to a particular arrangement of magnetic charges at the center of the Earth.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A *monopole* is an isolated magnetic charge, which has never been observed.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A *dipole* is equivalent to two opposing charges brought close together and a *quadrupole* to two dipoles brought together.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A quadrupole field is shown in the lower figure on the right.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Spherical harmonics can represent any scalar field (function of position) that satisfies certain properties.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A magnetic field is a vector field, but if it is expressed in Cartesian components *X, Y, Z*, each component is the derivative of the same scalar function called the *magnetic potential*.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Analyses of the Earth's magnetic field use a modified version of the usual spherical harmonics that differ by a multiplicative factor.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A least-squares fit to the magnetic field measurements gives the Earth's field as the sum of spherical harmonics, each multiplied by the best-fitting *Gauss coefficient* *gm*ℓ or *hm*ℓ.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The lowest-degree Gauss coefficient, *g*00, gives the contribution of an isolated magnetic charge, so it is zero.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The next three coefficients – *g*10, *g*11, and *h*11 – determine the direction and magnitude of the dipole contribution.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The best fitting dipole is tilted at an angle of about 10° with respect to the rotational axis, as described earlier.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Spherical harmonic analysis can be used to distinguish internal from external sources if measurements are available at more than one height (for example, ground observatories and satellites).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] In that case, each term with coefficient *gm*ℓ or *hm*ℓ can be split into two terms: one that decreases with radius as 1/*r*ℓ+1 and one that *increases* with radius as *r*ℓ.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The increasing terms fit the external sources (currents in the ionosphere and magnetosphere).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] However, averaged over a few years the external contributions average to zero.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The remaining terms predict that the potential of a dipole source (ℓ=1) drops off as 1/*r*2.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The magnetic field, being a derivative of the potential, drops off as 1/*r*3.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Quadrupole terms drop off as 1/*r*4, and higher order terms drop off increasingly rapidly with the radius.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The radius of the outer core is about half of the radius of the Earth.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] If the field at the core-mantle boundary is fit to spherical harmonics, the dipole part is smaller by a factor of about 8 at the surface, the quadrupole part by a factor of 16, and so on.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Thus, only the components with large wavelengths can be noticeable at the surface.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] From a variety of arguments, it is usually assumed that only terms up to degree 14 or less have their origin in the core.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] These have wavelengths of about 2,000 km (1,200 mi) or less.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Smaller features are attributed to crustal anomalies.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The International Association of Geomagnetism and Aeronomy maintains a standard global field model called the International Geomagnetic Reference Field (IGRF).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The 11th-generation model, IGRF11, was developed using data from satellites (Ørsted, CHAMP and SAC-C) and a world network of geomagnetic observatories.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The spherical harmonic expansion was truncated at degree 10, with 120 coefficients, until 2000.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Subsequent models are truncated at degree 13 (195 coefficients).
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Another global field model, called the World Magnetic Model, is produced jointly by the United States National Centers for Environmental Information (formerly the National Geophysical Data Center) and the British Geological Survey.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] This model truncates at degree 12 (168 coefficients) with an approximate spatial resolution of 3,000 kilometers.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] The above models only take into account the "main field" at the core-mantle boundary.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Although generally good enough for navigation, higher-accuracy use cases require smaller-scale magnetic anomalies and other variations to be considered.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] For historical data about the main field, the IGRF may be used back to year 1900.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] A specialized GUFM1 model estimates back to year 1590 using ship's logs.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Paleomagnetic research has produced models dating back to 10,000 BCE.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Animals, including birds and turtles, can detect the Earth's magnetic field, and use the field to navigate during migration.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Some researchers have found that cows and wild deer tend to align their bodies north–south while relaxing, but not when the animals are under high-voltage power lines, suggesting that magnetism is responsible.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Other researchers reported in 2011 that they could not replicate those findings using different Google Earth images.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Very weak electromagnetic fields disrupt the magnetic compass used by European robins and other songbirds, which use the Earth's magnetic field to navigate.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] Neither power lines nor cellphone signals are to blame for the electromagnetic field effect on the birds; instead, the culprits have frequencies between 2 kHz and 5 MHz.
[src:geophysics/earth-s-magnetic-field] These include AM radio signals and ordinary electronic equipment that might be found in businesses or private homes.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Geodynamics is generally concerned with processes that move materials throughout the Earth.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] In the Earth's interior, movement happens when rocks melt or deform and flow in response to a stress field.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] This deformation may be brittle, elastic, or plastic, depending on the magnitude of the stress and the material's physical properties, especially the stress relaxation time scale.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Rocks are structurally and compositionally heterogeneous and are subjected to variable stresses, so it is common to see different types of deformation in close spatial and temporal proximity.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] When working with geological timescales and lengths, it is convenient to use the continuous medium approximation and equilibrium stress fields to consider the average response to average stress.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Experts in geodynamics commonly use data from geodetic GPS, InSAR, and seismology, along with numerical models, to study the evolution of the Earth's lithosphere, mantle and core.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Rocks and other geological materials experience strain according to three distinct modes, elastic, plastic, and brittle depending on the properties of the material and the magnitude of the stress field.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Stress is defined as the average force per unit area exerted on each part of the rock.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Pressure is the part of stress that changes the volume of a solid; shear stress changes the shape.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] If there is no shear, the fluid is in hydrostatic equilibrium.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Since, over long periods, rocks readily deform under pressure, the Earth is in hydrostatic equilibrium to a good approximation.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] The pressure on rock depends only on the weight of the rock above, and this depends on gravity and the density of the rock.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] In a body like the Moon, the density is almost constant, so a pressure profile is readily calculated.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] In the Earth, the compression of rocks with depth is significant, and an equation of state is needed to calculate changes in density of rock even when it is of uniform composition.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Elastic deformation is always reversible, which means that if the stress field associated with elastic deformation is removed, the material will return to its previous state.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Materials only behave elastically when the relative arrangement along the axis being considered of material components (e.g. atoms or crystals) remains unchanged.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] This means that the magnitude of the stress cannot exceed the yield strength of a material, and the time scale of the stress cannot approach the relaxation time of the material.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] If stress exceeds the yield strength of a material, bonds begin to break (and reform), which can lead to ductile or brittle deformation.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Ductile or plastic deformation happens when the temperature of a system is high enough so that a significant fraction of the material microstates (figure 1) are unbound, which means that a large fraction of the chemical bonds are in the process of being broken and reformed.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] During ductile deformation, this process of atomic rearrangement redistributes stress and strain towards equilibrium faster than they can accumulate.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Examples include bending of the lithosphere under volcanic islands or sedimentary basins, and bending at oceanic trenches.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Ductile deformation happens when transport processes such as diffusion and advection that rely on chemical bonds to be broken and reformed redistribute strain about as fast as it accumulates.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] When strain localizes faster than these relaxation processes can redistribute it, brittle deformation occurs.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] The mechanism for brittle deformation involves a positive feedback between the accumulation or propagation of defects especially those produced by strain in areas of high strain, and the localization of strain along these dislocations and fractures.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] In other words, any fracture, however small, tends to focus strain at its leading edge, which causes the fracture to extend.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] In general, the mode of deformation is controlled not only by the amount of stress, but also by the distribution of strain and strain associated features.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Whichever mode of deformation ultimately occurs is the result of a competition between processes that tend to localize strain, such as fracture propagation, and relaxational processes, such as annealing, that tend to delocalize strain.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Structural geologists study the results of deformation, using observations of rock, especially the mode and geometry of deformation to reconstruct the stress field that affected the rock over time.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Structural geology is an important complement to geodynamics because it provides the most direct source of data about the movements of the Earth.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Different modes of deformation result in distinct geological structures, e.g. brittle fracture in rocks or ductile folding.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] The physical characteristics of rocks that control the rate and mode of strain, such as yield strength or viscosity, depend on the thermodynamic state of the rock and composition.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] The most important thermodynamic variables in this case are temperature and pressure.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Both of these increase with depth, so to a first approximation the mode of deformation can be understood in terms of depth.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Within the upper lithosphere, brittle deformation is common because under low pressure rocks have relatively low brittle strength, while at the same time low temperature reduces the likelihood of ductile flow.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] After the brittle-ductile transition zone, ductile deformation becomes dominant.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Elastic deformation happens when the time scale of stress is shorter than the relaxation time for the material.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Seismic waves are a common example of this type of deformation.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] At temperatures high enough to melt rocks, the ductile shear strength approaches zero, which is why shear mode elastic deformation (S-Waves) will not propagate through melts.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] The main motive force behind stress in the Earth is provided by thermal energy from radioisotope decay, friction, and residual heat.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Cooling at the surface and heat production within the Earth create a metastable thermal gradient from the hot core to the relatively cool lithosphere.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] This thermal energy is converted into mechanical energy by thermal expansion.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Deeper and hotter rocks often have higher thermal expansion and lower density relative to overlying rocks.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Conversely, rock that is cooled at the surface can become less buoyant than the rock below it.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Eventually this can lead to a Rayleigh-Taylor instability (Figure 2), or interpenetration of rock on different sides of the buoyancy contrast.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Negative thermal buoyancy of the oceanic plates is the primary cause of subduction and plate tectonics, while positive thermal buoyancy may lead to mantle plumes, which could explain intraplate volcanism.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] The relative importance of heat production vs. heat loss for buoyant convection throughout the whole Earth remains uncertain and understanding the details of buoyant convection is a key focus of geodynamics.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Geodynamics is a broad field which combines observations from many different types of geological study into a broad picture of the dynamics of Earth.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Close to the surface of the Earth, data includes field observations, geodesy, radiometric dating, petrology, mineralogy, drilling boreholes and remote sensing techniques.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] However, beyond a few kilometers depth, most of these kinds of observations become impractical.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Geologists studying the geodynamics of the mantle and core must rely entirely on remote sensing, especially seismology, and experimentally recreating the conditions found in the Earth in high pressure high temperature experiments.(see also Adams–Williamson equation).
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Because of the complexity of geological systems, computer modeling is used to test theoretical predictions about geodynamics using data from these sources.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] There are two main ways of geodynamic numerical modeling.
[src:geophysics/geodynamics] Modelling to produce basic fluid dynamics: This approach aims to answer how a specific system works in general.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] It is one of the oldest sciences, dating back to antiquity with the development of early seismometers and magnetic compasses, and later extending to Newtonian analyses of tides, precession, and Earth’s physical properties.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Geophysics integrates theory, observation, and experiment to investigate Earth and planetary systems across diverse spatial and temporal scales.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Its methods include field measurements, laboratory experiments, remote sensing, numerical modelling, and data analysis of both natural and instrumented records, including signal processing.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] As a unifying physical framework for Earth and planetary studies, geophysics connects phenomena from the deep interior to the upper atmosphere and near-space environment, providing the basis for understanding of planetary evolution, dynamics, and habitability.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Geophysics is a highly interdisciplinary subject, and geophysicists contribute to every area of the Earth sciences, while some geophysicists conduct research in the planetary sciences.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] To provide a more clear idea on what constitutes geophysics, this section describes phenomena that are studied in physics and how they relate to the Earth and its surroundings.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Geophysicists also investigate the physical processes and properties of the Earth, its fluid layers, and magnetic field along with the near-Earth environment in the Solar System, which includes other planetary bodies.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The gravitational pull of the Moon and Sun gives rise to two high tides and two low tides every lunar day, or every 24 hours and 50 minutes.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Therefore, there is a gap of 12 hours and 25 minutes between every high tide and between every low tide.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Gravitational forces make rocks press down on deeper rocks, increasing their density as the depth increases.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Measurements of gravitational acceleration and gravitational potential at the Earth's surface and above it can be used to look for mineral deposits (see gravity anomaly and gravimetry).
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The surface gravitational field provides information on the dynamics of tectonic plates.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The geopotential surface called the geoid is one definition of the shape of the Earth.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The geoid would be the global mean sea level if the oceans were in equilibrium and could be extended through the continents (such as with very narrow canals).
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Seismic waves are vibrations that travel through the Earth's interior or along its surface.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The entire Earth can also oscillate in forms that are called normal modes or free oscillations of the Earth.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Ground motions from waves or normal modes are measured using seismographs.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] If the waves come from a localized source such as an earthquake or explosion, measurements at more than one location can be used to locate the source.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The locations of earthquakes provide information on plate tectonics and mantle convection.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Recording of seismic waves from controlled sources provides information on the region that the waves travel through.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] If the density or composition of the rock changes, waves are reflected.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Reflections recorded using Reflection Seismology can provide a wealth of information on the structure of the earth up to several kilometers deep and are used to increase our understanding of the geology as well as to explore for oil and gas.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Changes in the travel direction, called refraction, can be used to infer the deep structure of the Earth.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Understanding their mechanisms, which depend on the type of earthquake (e.g., intraplate or deep focus), can lead to better estimates of earthquake risk and improvements in earthquake engineering.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] There is always a downward electric field near the surface that averages 120 volts per meter.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The galactic cosmic rays penetrating the atmosphere result in its ionization relative to the solid Earth, leaving it with a net positive charge.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] A current of about 1800 amperes flows in the global circuit.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] It flows downward from the ionosphere over most of the Earth and back upwards through thunderstorms.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The flow is manifested by lightning below the clouds and sprites above.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] A variety of electric methods are used in geophysical survey.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Some measure spontaneous potential, a potential that arises in the ground because of human-made or natural disturbances.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Telluric currents flow in Earth and the oceans.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] They have two causes: electromagnetic induction by the time-varying, external-origin geomagnetic field and motion of conducting bodies (such as seawater) across the Earth's permanent magnetic field.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The distribution of telluric current density can be used to detect variations in electrical resistivity of underground structures.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Geophysicists can also provide the electric current themselves (see induced polarization and electrical resistivity tomography).
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Electromagnetic waves occur in the ionosphere and magnetosphere as well as in Earth's outer core.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Dawn chorus is believed to be caused by high-energy electrons that get caught in the Van Allen radiation belt.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Whistlers are produced by lightning strikes.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Electromagnetic waves may also be generated by earthquakes (see seismo-electromagnetics).
[src:geophysics/geophysics] In the highly conductive liquid iron of the outer core, magnetic fields are generated by electric currents through electromagnetic induction.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Alfvén waves are magnetohydrodynamic waves in the magnetosphere or the Earth's core.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] In the core, they probably have little observable effect on the Earth's magnetic field, but slower waves such as magnetic Rossby waves may be one source of geomagnetic secular variation.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Electromagnetic methods that are used for geophysical survey include transient electromagnetics, magnetotellurics, surface nuclear magnetic resonance and electromagnetic seabed logging.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The Earth's magnetic field protects the Earth from the deadly solar wind and has long been used for navigation.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] It originates in the fluid motions of the outer core.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The magnetic field in the upper atmosphere gives rise to the auroras.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The Earth's field is roughly like a tilted dipole, but it changes over time (a phenomenon called geomagnetic secular variation).
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Mostly the geomagnetic pole stays near the geographic pole, but at random intervals averaging 440,000 to a million years or so, the polarity of the Earth's field reverses.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Geologists observed geomagnetic reversal recorded in volcanic rocks, through magnetostratigraphy correlation (see natural remanent magnetization) and their signature can be seen as parallel linear magnetic anomaly stripes on the seafloor.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] These stripes provide quantitative information on seafloor spreading, a part of plate tectonics.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] They are the basis of magnetostratigraphy, which correlates magnetic reversals with other stratigraphies to construct geologic time scales.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] In addition, the magnetization in rocks can be used to measure the motion of continents.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Radioactive decay accounts for about 80% of the Earth's internal heat, powering the geodynamo and plate tectonics.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The main heat-producing isotopes are potassium-40, uranium-238, uranium-235, and thorium-232.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Radioactive elements are used for radiometric dating, the primary method for establishing an absolute time scale in geochronology.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Unstable isotopes decay at predictable rates, and the decay rates of different isotopes cover several orders of magnitude, so radioactive decay can be used to accurately date both recent events and events in past geologic eras.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Radiometric mapping using ground and airborne gamma spectrometry can be used to map the concentration and distribution of radioisotopes near the Earth's surface, which is useful for mapping lithology and alteration.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Fluid motions occur in the magnetosphere, atmosphere, ocean, mantle and core.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Even the mantle, though it has an enormous viscosity, flows like a fluid over long time intervals.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] This flow is reflected in phenomena such as isostasy, post-glacial rebound and mantle plumes.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The mantle flow drives plate tectonics and the flow in the Earth's core drives the geodynamo.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Geophysical fluid dynamics is a primary tool in physical oceanography and meteorology.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The rotation of the Earth has profound effects on the Earth's fluid dynamics, often due to the Coriolis effect.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] In the atmosphere, it gives rise to large-scale patterns like Rossby waves and determines the basic circulation patterns of storms.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] In the ocean, they drive large-scale circulation patterns as well as Kelvin waves and Ekman spirals at the ocean surface.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] In the Earth's core, the circulation of the molten iron is structured by Taylor columns.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Waves and other phenomena in the magnetosphere can be modeled using magnetohydrodynamics.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The Earth is cooling, and the resulting heat flow generates the Earth's magnetic field through the geodynamo and plate tectonics through mantle convection.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The main sources of heat are: primordial heat due to Earth's cooling and radioactivity in the planets upper crust.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] There is also some contributions from phase transitions.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Heat is mostly carried to the surface by thermal convection, although there are two thermal boundary layers – the core–mantle boundary and the lithosphere – in which heat is transported by conduction.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Some heat is carried up from the bottom of the mantle by mantle plumes.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The heat flow at the Earth's surface is about 4.2 × 1013 W, and it is a potential source of geothermal energy.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The physical properties of minerals must be understood to infer the composition of the Earth's interior from seismology, the geothermal gradient and other sources of information.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Mineral physicists study the elastic properties of minerals; their high-pressure phase diagrams, melting points and equations of state at high pressure; and the rheological properties of rocks, or their ability to flow.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Deformation of rocks by creep make flow possible, although over short times the rocks are brittle.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The viscosity of rocks is affected by temperature and pressure, and in turn, determines the rates at which tectonic plates move.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Water is a very complex substance and its unique properties are essential for life.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Its physical properties shape the hydrosphere and are an essential part of the water cycle and climate.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Its thermodynamic properties determine evaporation and the thermal gradient in the atmosphere.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The many types of precipitation involve a complex mixture of processes such as coalescence, supercooling and supersaturation.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Some precipitated water becomes groundwater, and groundwater flow includes phenomena such as percolation, while the conductivity of water makes electrical and electromagnetic methods useful for tracking groundwater flow.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Physical properties of water such as salinity have a large effect on its motion in the oceans.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The many phases of ice form the cryosphere and come in forms like ice sheets, glaciers, sea ice, freshwater ice, snow, and frozen ground (or permafrost).
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Contrary to popular belief, the earth is not entirely spherical but instead generally exhibits an ellipsoid shape- which is a result of the centrifugal forces the planet generates due to its constant motion.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] These forces cause the planets diameter to bulge towards the Equator and results in the ellipsoid shape.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Evidence from seismology, heat flow at the surface, and mineral physics is combined with the Earth's mass and moment of inertia to infer the composition, density, temperature, and pressure of the Earth's interior.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] For example, the Earth's mean specific gravity (5.515) is far higher than the typical specific gravity of rocks at the surface (2.7–3.3), implying that the deeper material is denser.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] This is also implied by its low moment of inertia ( 0.33 *M R*2, compared to 0.4 *M R*2 for a sphere of constant density).
[src:geophysics/geophysics] However, some of the density increase is compression under the enormous pressures inside the Earth.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The effect of pressure can be calculated using the Adams–Williamson equation.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The conclusion is that pressure alone cannot account for the increase in density.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Instead, we know that the Earth's core is composed of an alloy of iron and other minerals.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Reconstructions of seismic waves in the deep interior of the Earth show that there are no S-waves in the outer core.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] This indicates that the outer core is liquid, because liquids cannot support shear.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The outer core is liquid, and the motion of this highly conductive fluid generates the Earth's field.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Earth's inner core, however, is solid because of the enormous pressure.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Reconstruction of seismic reflections in the deep interior indicates some major discontinuities in seismic velocities that demarcate the major zones of the Earth: inner core, outer core, mantle, lithosphere and crust.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The mantle itself is divided into the upper mantle, transition zone, lower mantle and *D′′* layer.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Between the crust and the mantle is the Mohorovičić discontinuity.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The seismic model of the Earth does not by itself determine the composition of the layers.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] For a complete model of the Earth, mineral physics is needed to interpret seismic velocities in terms of composition.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The mineral properties are temperature-dependent, so the geotherm must also be determined.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] This requires physical theory for thermal conduction and convection and the heat contribution of radioactive elements.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The main model for the radial structure of the interior of the Earth is the preliminary reference Earth model (PREM).
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Some parts of this model have been updated by recent findings in mineral physics (see post-perovskite) and supplemented by seismic tomography.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The mantle is mainly composed of silicates, and the boundaries between layers of the mantle are consistent with phase transitions.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The mantle acts as a solid for seismic waves, but under high pressures and temperatures, it deforms so that over millions of years it acts like a liquid.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] If a planet's magnetic field is strong enough, its interaction with the solar wind forms a magnetosphere.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Early space probes mapped out the gross dimensions of the Earth's magnetic field, which extends about 10 Earth radii towards the Sun.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The solar wind, a stream of charged particles, streams out and around the terrestrial magnetic field, and continues behind the magnetic tail, hundreds of Earth radii downstream.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Inside the magnetosphere, there are relatively dense regions of solar wind particles called the Van Allen radiation belts.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Geophysical measurements are generally at a particular time and place.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Accurate measurements of position, along with earth deformation and gravity, are the province of geodesy.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] While geodesy and geophysics are separate fields, the two are so closely connected that many scientific organizations such as the American Geophysical Union, the Canadian Geophysical Union and the International Union of Geodesy and Geophysics encompass both.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Absolute positions are most frequently determined using the global positioning system (GPS).
[src:geophysics/geophysics] A three-dimensional position is calculated using messages from four or more visible satellites and referred to the 1980 Geodetic Reference System.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] An alternative, optical astronomy, combines astronomical coordinates and the local gravity vector to get geodetic coordinates.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] This method only provides the position in two coordinates and is more difficult to use than GPS.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] However, it is useful for measuring motions of the Earth such as nutation and Chandler wobble.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Relative positions of two or more points can be determined using very-long-baseline interferometry.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Gravity measurements became part of geodesy because they were needed to related measurements at the surface of the Earth to the reference coordinate system.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Gravity measurements on land can be made using gravimeters deployed either on the surface or in helicopter flyovers.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Since the 1960s, the Earth's gravity field has been measured by analyzing the motion of satellites.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Sea level can also be measured by satellites using radar altimetry, contributing to a more accurate geoid.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] In 2002, NASA launched the Gravity Recovery and Climate Experiment (GRACE), wherein two twin satellites map variations in Earth's gravity field by making measurements of the distance between the two satellites using GPS and a microwave ranging system.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Gravity variations detected by GRACE include those caused by changes in ocean currents; runoff and ground water depletion; melting ice sheets and glaciers.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Satellites in space have made it possible to collect data from not only the visible light region, but in other areas of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The planets can be characterized by their force fields: gravity and their magnetic fields, which are studied through geophysics and space physics.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Measuring the changes in acceleration experienced by spacecraft as they orbit has allowed fine details of the gravity fields of the planets to be mapped.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] For example, in the 1970s, the gravity field disturbances above lunar maria were measured through lunar orbiters, which led to the discovery of concentrations of mass, mascons, beneath the Imbrium, Serenitatis, Crisium, Nectaris and Humorum basins.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Since geophysics is concerned with the shape of the Earth, and by extension the mapping of features around and in the planet, geophysical measurements include high accuracy GPS measurements.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] These measurements are processed to increase their accuracy through differential GPS processing.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Once the geophysical measurements have been processed and inverted, the interpreted results are plotted using GIS.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Programs such as ArcGIS and Geosoft were built to meet these needs and include many geophysical functions that are built-in, such as upward continuation, and the calculation of the measurement derivative such as the first-vertical derivative.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Many geophysics companies have designed in-house geophysics programs that pre-date ArcGIS and GeoSoft in order to meet the visualization requirements of a geophysical dataset.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Exploration geophysics is a branch of applied geophysics that involves the development and utilization of different seismic or electromagnetic methods which the aim of investigating different energy, mineral and water resources.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] This is done through the uses of various remote sensing platforms such as; satellites, aircraft, boats, drones, borehole sensing equipment and seismic receivers.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] These equipment are often used in conjunction with different geophysical methods such as magnetic, gravimetry, electromagnetic, radiometric, barometry methods in order to gather the data.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The remote sensing platforms used in exploration geophysics are not perfect and need adjustments done on them in order to accurately account for the effects that the platform itself may have on the collected data.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] For example, when gathering aeromagnetic data (aircraft gathered magnetic data) using a conventional fixed-wing aircraft- the platform has to be adjusted to account for the electromagnetic currents that it may generate as it passes through Earth's magnetic field.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] There are also corrections related to changes in measured potential field intensity as the Earth rotates, as the Earth orbits the Sun, and as the moon orbits the Earth.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Geophysical measurements are often recorded as time-series with GPS location.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Signal processing involves the correction of time-series data for unwanted noise or errors introduced by the measurement platform, such as aircraft vibrations in gravity data.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] It also involves the reduction of sources of noise, such as diurnal corrections in magnetic data.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Geophysics emerged as a separate discipline only in the 19th century, from the intersection of physical geography, geology, astronomy, meteorology, and physics.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The first known use of the word *geophysics* was in German ("Geophysik") by Julius Fröbel in 1834.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] However, many geophysical phenomena – such as the Earth's magnetic field and earthquakes – have been investigated since the ancient era.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The magnetic compass existed in China back as far as the fourth century BC.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] It was used as much for feng shui as for navigation on land.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] It was not until good steel needles could be forged that compasses were used for navigation at sea; before that, they could not retain their magnetism long enough to be useful.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The first mention of a compass in Europe was in 1190 AD.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] In circa 240 BC, Eratosthenes of Cyrene deduced that the Earth was round and measured the circumference of Earth with great precision.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] He developed a system of latitude and longitude.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Perhaps the earliest contribution to seismology was the invention of a seismoscope by the prolific inventor Zhang Heng in 132 AD.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] This instrument was designed to drop a bronze ball from the mouth of a dragon into the mouth of a toad.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] By looking at which of eight toads had the ball, one could determine the direction of the earthquake.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] It was 1571 years before the first design for a seismoscope was published in Europe, by Jean de la Hautefeuille.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The 17th century had major milestones that marked the beginning of modern science.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] In 1600, William Gilbert release a publication titled *De Magnete* (1600) where he conducted series of experiments on both natural magnets (called 'loadstones') and artificially magnetized iron.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] His experiments lead to observations involving a small compass needle (versorium) which replicated magnetic behaviours when subjected to a spherical magnet, along with it experiencing 'magnetic dips' when it was pivoted on a horizontal axis.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] HIs findings led to the deduction that compasses point north due to the Earth itself being a giant magnet.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] In 1687 Isaac Newton published his work titled *Principia* which was pivotal in the development of modern scientific fields such as astronomy and physics.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] In it, Newton both laid the foundations for classical mechanics and gravitation, as well as explained different geophysical phenomena such as the precession of the equinox (the orbit of whole star patterns along an ecliptic axis.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] Newton's theory of gravity had gained so much success, that it resulted in changing the main objective of physics in that era to unravel natures fundamental forces, and their characterizations in laws.
[src:geophysics/geophysics] The first seismometer, an instrument capable of keeping a continuous record of seismic activity, was built by James Forbes in 1844.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Gravity is usually measured in units of acceleration.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] In the SI system of units, the standard unit of acceleration is metres per second squared (m/s2).
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Other units include the cgs gal (sometimes known as a *galileo*, in either case with symbol Gal), which equals 1 centimetre per second squared, and the *g* (*g*n), equal to 9.80665 m/s2.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The value of the *g*n is defined as approximately equal to the acceleration due to gravity at the Earth's surface, although the actual acceleration varies slightly by location.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] A **gravimeter** is an instrument used to measure gravitational acceleration.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Every mass has an associated gravitational potential.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The gradient of this potential is a force.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] A gravimeter measures this gravitational force.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] For a small body, general relativity predicts gravitational effects indistinguishable from the effects of acceleration by the equivalence principle.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Thus, gravimeters can be regarded as special-purpose accelerometers.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Many weighing scales may be regarded as simple gravimeters.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] In one common form, a spring is used to counteract the force of gravity pulling on an object.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The change in length of the spring may be calibrated to the force required to balance the gravitational pull.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The resulting measurement may be made in units of force (such as the newton), however, gravimeters display their measurements in units of gals (cm/s2), and parts per million, parts per billion, or parts per trillion of the average vertical acceleration with respect to the Earth.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Though similar in design to other accelerometers, gravimeters are typically designed to be much more sensitive.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Their first uses were to measure the changes in gravity from the varying densities and distribution of masses inside the Earth, from temporal tidal variations in the shape and distribution of mass in the oceans, atmosphere and earth.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The resolution of gravimeters can be increased by averaging samples over longer periods.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Fundamental characteristics of gravimeters are the accuracy of a single measurement (a single *sample*) and the sampling rate.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Besides precision, stability is also an important property for a gravimeter as it allows the monitoring of gravity *changes*.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] These changes can be the result of mass displacements inside the Earth, or of vertical movements of the Earth's crust on which measurements are being made.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The first gravimeters were vertical accelerometers, specialized for measuring the constant downward acceleration of gravity on the Earth's surface.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The Earth's vertical gravity varies from place to place over its surface by about ±0.5%.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] It varies by about ±1000 ⁠nm/s2⁠ (nanometers per second squared) at any location because of the changing positions of the Sun and Moon relative to the Earth.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The majority of modern gravimeters use specially designed metal or quartz zero-length springs to support the test mass.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The special property of these springs is that the natural resonant period of oscillation of the spring–mass system can be made very long – approaching a thousand seconds.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] This detunes the test mass from most local vibration and mechanical noise, increasing the sensitivity and utility of the gravimeter.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Quartz and metal springs are chosen for different reasons; quartz springs are less affected by magnetic and electric fields while metal springs have a much lower drift due to elongation over time.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The test mass is sealed in an air-tight container so that tiny changes of barometric pressure from blowing wind and other weather do not change the buoyancy of the test mass in air.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Spring gravimeters are, in practice, relative instruments that measure the difference in gravity between different locations.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] A relative instrument also requires calibration by comparing instrument readings taken at locations with known absolute values of gravity.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Researchers use more sophisticated gravimeters when precise measurements are needed.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] When measuring Earth's gravitational field, measurements are made to the precision of microgals to find density variations in the rocks making up the Earth.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Several types of gravimeters exist for making these measurements, including some that are essentially refined versions of the spring scale described above.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] These measurements are used to quantify gravity anomalies.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Gravimeters can detect vibrations and gravity changes from human activities.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Depending on the interests of the researcher or operator, this might be counteracted by integral vibration isolation and signal processing.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Gravimeters have been designed to mount in vehicles, including aircraft (note the field of aerogravity), ships and submarines.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] These special gravimeters isolate acceleration from the vehicle's movement and subtract it from measurements.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The acceleration of the vehicles is often hundreds or thousands of times stronger than the changes in gravity being measured.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The Lunar Surface Gravimeter was deployed on the surface of the Moon during the 1972 Apollo 17 mission but did not work due to a design error.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] A second device carried on the same mission, the Lunar Traverse Gravimeter, functioned as anticipated.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Gravimeters are used for petroleum and mineral prospecting, seismology, geodesy, geophysical surveys and other geophysical research, and for metrology.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Their fundamental purpose is to map the gravity field in space and time.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Most current work is Earth-based, with a few satellites around Earth, but gravimeters are also applicable to the Moon, Sun, planets, asteroids, stars, galaxies and other bodies.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Gravitational wave experiments monitor the changes with time in the gravitational potential itself, rather than the gradient of the potential that the gravimeter is tracking.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The subsystems of the gravitational radiation experiments are very sensitive to changes in the gradient of the potential.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The local gravity signals on Earth that interfere with gravitational wave experiments are disparagingly referred to as "Newtonian noise", since Newtonian gravity calculations are sufficient to characterize many of the local (earth-based) signals.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] A common type of portable gravimeter measures the acceleration of small masses free falling in a vacuum while the accelerometer is firmly attached to the ground.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The mass includes a retroreflector and terminates one arm of a Michelson interferometer.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] By counting and timing the interference fringes, the acceleration of the mass can be measured.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] A more recent development is a *rise and fall* version that tosses the mass upward and measures both upward and downward motion.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] This allows cancellation of some measurement errors.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Absolute gravimeters are used in the calibration of relative gravimeters, surveying for gravity anomalies (e.g. voids), and for establishing the vertical geodetic control network.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Atom interferometric and atomic fountain methods are used for precise measurement of the Earth's gravity, and atomic clocks and purpose-built instruments can use time dilation measurements to track changes in the gravitational potential and gravitational acceleration on the Earth.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The most common gravimeters are spring-based.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] They are used in gravity surveys over large areas for establishing the figure of the geoid over those areas.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] They are basically a weight on a spring, and by measuring the amount by which the weight stretches the spring, local gravity can be measured.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] However, the strength of the spring must be calibrated by placing the instrument in a location with a known gravitational acceleration.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The superconducting gravimeter achieves sensitivities of 10–11 m·s−2 (one nanogal), approximately one trillionth (10−12) of the Earth surface gravity.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] In a demonstration of the sensitivity of the SG, Virtanen (2006), describes how an instrument at Metsähovi, Finland, detected the gradual increase in surface gravity as workmen cleared snow from its laboratory roof.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The largest component of the signal recorded by a SG is the tidal gravity of the Sun and Moon acting at the station.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] This is roughly ±1000 ⁠nm/s2⁠ (nanometers per second squared) at most locations.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Many of the broadband three-axis seismometers in common use are sensitive enough to track the Sun and Moon.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] When operated to report acceleration, they are useful gravimeters.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Because they have three axes, it is possible to solve for their position and orientation, by either tracking the arrival time and pattern of seismic waves from earthquakes, or by referencing them to the Sun and Moon tidal gravity.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Recently, the SGs, and broadband three-axis seismometers operated in gravimeter mode, have begun to detect and characterize the small gravity signals from earthquakes.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] These signals arrive at the gravimeter at the speed of light, so have the potential to improve earthquake early warning methods.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] There is some activity to design purpose-built gravimeters of sufficient sensitivity and bandwidth to detect these prompt gravity signals from earthquakes.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Newer MEMS gravimeters, *atom gravimeters*, offer the potential for low-cost arrays of sensors.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] MEMS gravimeters are currently variations on spring-type accelerometers where the motions of a tiny cantilever or mass are tracked to report acceleration.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Much of the research is focused on different methods of detecting the position and movements of these small masses.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] In atom gravimeters, the mass is a collection of atoms.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Transportable relative gravimeters also exist; they employ an extremely stable inertial platform to compensate for the masking effects of motion and vibration, a difficult engineering feat.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The first transportable relative gravimeters were, reportedly, a secret military technology developed in the 1950–1960s as a navigational aid for nuclear submarines.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Subsequently in the 1980s, transportable relative gravimeters were reverse engineered by the civilian sector for use on ships, then in air and finally satellite-borne gravity surveys.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Microgravimetry is an important branch developed on the foundation of classical gravimetry.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Microgravity investigations are carried out in order to solve various problems of engineering geology, mainly locating voids and their monitoring.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Very detailed measurements of high accuracy can indicate voids of any origin, provided the size and depth are large enough to produce a measurable gravity effect.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Jean Richer was the first person to observe a change in gravitational force over the surface of the Earth.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The modern gravimeter was developed by Lucien LaCoste and Arnold Romberg in 1936.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] They also invented most subsequent refinements, including the ship-mounted gravimeter in 1965, temperature-resistant instruments for deep boreholes, and lightweight hand-carried instruments.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Most of their designs remain in use with refinements in data collection and data processing.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Currently, the static and time-variable Earth's gravity field parameters are determined using modern satellite missions, such as GOCE, CHAMP, Swarm, GRACE and GRACE-FO.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] The lowest-degree parameters, including the Earth's oblateness and geocenter motion are best determined with satellite laser ranging.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Large-scale gravity anomalies can be detected from space, as a by-product of satellite gravity missions.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Gravity Recovery and Climate Experiment (GRACE) consisted of two satellites that detected gravitational changes across the Earth.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] These changes could be presented as gravity anomaly temporal variations.
[src:geophysics/gravimetry] Gravity Recovery and Interior Laboratory (GRAIL) also consisted of two spacecraft orbiting the Moon for three years before their deorbit in 2015.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Earth's lithosphere, the rigid outer shell of the planet including the crust and upper mantle, is fractured into seven or eight major plates (depending on how they are defined) and many minor plates or "platelets".
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Where the plates meet, their relative motion determines the type of plate boundary (or fault): *convergent*, *divergent*, or *transform*.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The relative movement of the plates typically ranges from zero to 10 cm annually.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Faults tend to be geologically active, with earthquakes, volcanic activity, mountain-building, and oceanic trench formation.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Tectonic plates are composed of the oceanic lithosphere and the thicker continental lithosphere, each topped by its own kind of crust.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Along convergent plate boundaries, the process of subduction carries the edge of one plate down under the other plate and into the mantle.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] This process reduces the total surface area (crust) of Earth.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The lost surface is balanced by the formation of new oceanic crust along divergent margins by seafloor spreading, keeping the total surface area constant in a tectonic "conveyor belt".
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] While Earth is the only planet known to currently have active plate tectonics, evidence suggests that other planets and moons have experienced or exhibit forms of tectonic activity.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Jupiter's moon Europa shows signs of ice crustal plates moving and interacting, similar to Earth's plate tectonics.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Mars and Venus are thought to have had tectonic activity in the past, though not of the same form as Earth.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Tectonic plates are relatively rigid and float across the ductile asthenosphere beneath.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Lateral density variations in the mantle result in convection currents, the slow creeping motion of Earth's solid mantle.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] At a seafloor spreading ridge, plates move away from the ridge, which is a topographic high, and the newly formed crust cools as it moves away, increasing its density and contributing to the motion.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] At a subduction zone, the relatively cold, dense oceanic crust sinks down into the mantle, forming the downward convecting limb of a mantle cell, which is the strongest driver of plate motion.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The relative importance and interaction of other proposed factors such as active convection, upwelling inside the mantle, and tidal drag of the Moon are subjects of debate.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The outer layers of Earth are divided into the lithosphere and asthenosphere.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The division is based on differences in mechanical properties and in the method for the transfer of heat.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The lithosphere is cooler and more rigid, while the asthenosphere is hotter and flows more easily.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] In terms of heat transfer, the lithosphere loses heat by conduction, whereas the asthenosphere also transfers heat by convection and has a nearly adiabatic temperature gradient.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The key principle of plate tectonics is that the lithosphere exists as separate and distinct tectonic plates, which ride on the viscoelastic asthenosphere.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Plate motions range from 10 to 40 millimetres per year (0.4 to 1.6 in/year) at the Mid-Atlantic Ridge (about as fast as fingernails grow), to about 160 millimetres per year (6.3 in/year) for the Nazca plate (about as fast as hair grows).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Tectonic lithospheric plates consist of lithospheric mantle overlain by one or two types of crustal material: oceanic crust (in older texts called *sima* from silicon and magnesium) and continental crust (*sial* from silicon and aluminium).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The distinction between oceanic crust and continental crust is based on their modes of formation.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Oceanic crust is formed at sea-floor spreading centers.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Continental crust is formed through arc volcanism and accretion of terranes through plate tectonic processes.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Oceanic crust is denser than continental crust because it has less silicon and more of the heavier elements than continental crust.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] As a result of this density difference, oceanic crust generally lies below sea level, while continental crust buoyantly projects above sea level.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Average oceanic lithosphere is typically 100 km (62 mi) thick.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] As time passes, it cools by conducting heat from below, and releasing it radiatively into space.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The adjacent mantle below is cooled by this process and added to its base.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Because it is formed at mid-ocean ridges and spreads outwards, its thickness is therefore a function of its distance from the mid-ocean ridge where it was formed.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] For a typical distance that oceanic lithosphere must travel before being subducted, the thickness varies from about 6 km (4 mi) thick at mid-ocean ridges to greater than 100 km (62 mi) at subduction zones.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] For shorter or longer distances, the subduction zone, and therefore also the mean, thickness becomes smaller or larger, respectively.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Continental lithosphere is typically about 200 km (120 mi) thick, though this varies considerably between basins, mountain ranges, and stable cratonic interiors of continents.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The location where two plates meet is called a *plate boundary*.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Plate boundaries are where geological events occur, such as earthquakes and the creation of topographic features such as mountains, volcanoes, mid-ocean ridges, and oceanic trenches.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The vast majority of the world's active volcanoes occur along plate boundaries, with the Pacific plate's Ring of Fire being the most active and widely known.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Some volcanoes occur in the interiors of plates, and these have been variously attributed to internal plate deformation and to mantle plumes.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Tectonic plates may include continental crust or oceanic crust, or both.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] For example, the African plate includes the continent and parts of the floor of the Atlantic and Indian Oceans.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Some pieces of oceanic crust, known as ophiolites, failed to be subducted under continental crust at destructive plate boundaries; instead, these oceanic crustal fragments were pushed upward and were preserved within continental crust.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Three types of plate boundaries exist, characterized by the way the plates move relative to each other.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] They are associated with different types of surface phenomena.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Subduction zones are of two types: ocean-to-continent subduction, where the dense oceanic lithosphere plunges beneath the less dense continent, or ocean-to-ocean subduction where older, cooler, denser oceanic crust slips beneath less dense oceanic crust.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Deep marine trenches are typically associated with subduction zones, and the basins that develop along the active boundary are often called "foreland basins".
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The addition of water lowers the melting point of the mantle material above the subducting slab, causing it to melt.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The magma that results typically leads to volcanism.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] At zones of ocean-to-ocean subduction a deep trench forms in an arc shape.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] At continental collision zones there are two masses of continental lithosphere converging.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Since they are of similar density, neither is subducted.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The plate edges are compressed, folded, and uplifted forming mountain ranges, e.g.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Closure of ocean basins can occur at continent-to-continent boundaries.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Tectonic plates are able to move because of the relative density of oceanic lithosphere and the relative weakness of the asthenosphere.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Dissipation of heat from the mantle is the original source of the energy required to drive plate tectonics through convection or large scale upwelling and doming.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] As a consequence, a powerful source generating plate motion is the excess density of the oceanic lithosphere sinking in subduction zones.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] When the new crust forms at mid-ocean ridges, this oceanic lithosphere is initially less dense than the underlying asthenosphere, but it becomes denser with age as it conductively cools and thickens.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The greater density of old lithosphere relative to the underlying asthenosphere allows it to sink into the deep mantle at subduction zones, providing most of the driving force for plate movement.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The weakness of the asthenosphere allows the tectonic plates to move easily towards a subduction zone.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] For much of the first quarter of the 20th century, the leading theory of the driving force behind tectonic plate motions envisaged large scale convection currents in the upper mantle, which can be transmitted through the asthenosphere.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] This theory was launched by Arthur Holmes and some forerunners in the 1930s and was immediately recognized as the solution for the acceptance of the theory as originally discussed in the papers of Alfred Wegener in the early years of the 20th century.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] However, despite its acceptance, it was long debated in the scientific community because the leading theory still envisaged a static Earth without moving continents up until the major breakthroughs of the early sixties.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Two- and three-dimensional imaging of Earth's interior (seismic tomography) shows a varying lateral density distribution throughout the mantle.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Such density variations can be material (from rock chemistry), mineral (from variations in mineral structures), or thermal (through thermal expansion and contraction from heat energy).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The manifestation of this varying lateral density is mantle convection from buoyancy forces.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] How mantle convection directly and indirectly relates to plate motion is a matter of ongoing study and discussion in geodynamics.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Somehow, this energy must be transferred to the lithosphere for tectonic plates to move.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] There are essentially two main types of mechanisms that are thought to exist related to the dynamics of the mantle that influence plate motion which are primary (through the large scale convection cells) or secondary.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The secondary mechanisms view plate motion driven by friction between the convection currents in the asthenosphere and the more rigid overlying lithosphere.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] This is due to the inflow of mantle material related to the downward pull on plates in subduction zones at ocean trenches.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Slab pull may occur in a geodynamic setting where basal tractions continue to act on the plate as it dives into the mantle (although perhaps to a greater extent acting on both the under and upper side of the slab).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Furthermore, slabs that are broken off and sink into the mantle can cause viscous mantle forces driving plates through slab suction.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] In the theory of plume tectonics followed by numerous researchers during the 1990s, a modified concept of mantle convection currents is used.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] It asserts that super plumes rise from the deeper mantle and are the drivers or substitutes of the major convection cells.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] These ideas find their roots in the early 1930s in the works of Beloussov and van Bemmelen, which were initially opposed to plate tectonics and placed the mechanism in a fixed frame of vertical movements.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Van Bemmelen later modified the concept in his "Undation Models" and used "Mantle Blisters" as the driving force for horizontal movements, invoking gravitational forces away from the regional crustal doming.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The mechanism is still advocated to explain the break-up of supercontinents during specific geological epochs.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] It has followers amongst the scientists involved in the theory of Earth expansion.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Another theory is that the mantle flows neither in cells nor large plumes but rather as a series of channels just below Earth's crust, which then provide basal friction to the lithosphere.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] This theory, called "surge tectonics", was popularized during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Recent research, based on three-dimensional computer modelling, suggests that plate geometry is governed by a feedback between mantle convection patterns and the strength of the lithosphere.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Forces related to gravity are invoked as secondary phenomena within the framework of a more general driving mechanism such as the various forms of mantle dynamics described above.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] In modern views, gravity is invoked as the major driving force, through slab pull along subduction zones.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Gravitational sliding away from a spreading ridge is one of the proposed driving forces: plate motion is driven by the higher elevation of plates at ocean ridges.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] As oceanic lithosphere is formed at spreading ridges from hot mantle material, it gradually cools and thickens with age (and thus adds distance from the ridge).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Cool oceanic lithosphere is significantly denser than the hot mantle material from which it is derived and so with increasing thickness it gradually subsides into the mantle to compensate the greater load.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The result is a slight lateral incline with increased distance from the ridge axis.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] This force is regarded as a secondary force and is often referred to as "ridge push".
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] This is a misnomer as there is no force "pushing" horizontally, indeed tensional features are dominant along ridges.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] It is more accurate to refer to this mechanism as "gravitational sliding", since the topography across the whole plate can vary considerably and spreading ridges are only the most prominent feature.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Other mechanisms generating this gravitational secondary force include flexural bulging of the lithosphere before it dives underneath an adjacent plate, producing a clear topographical feature that can offset, or at least affect, the influence of topographical ocean ridges.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Mantle plumes and hot spots are also postulated to impinge on the underside of tectonic plates.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Slab pull: Scientific opinion is that the asthenosphere is insufficiently competent or rigid to directly cause motion by friction along the base of the lithosphere.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Slab pull is therefore most widely thought to be the greatest force acting on the plates.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] In this understanding, plate motion is mostly driven by the weight of cold, dense plates sinking into the mantle at trenches.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Recent models indicate that trench suction plays an important role as well.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] However, the fact that the North American plate is nowhere being subducted, although it is in motion, presents a problem.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The same holds for the African, Eurasian, and Antarctic plates.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Gravitational sliding away from mantle doming: According to older theories, one of the driving mechanisms of the plates is the existence of large scale asthenosphere/mantle domes which cause the gravitational sliding of lithosphere plates away from them (see the paragraph on Mantle Mechanisms).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] This gravitational sliding represents a secondary phenomenon of this basically vertically oriented mechanism.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] It finds its roots in the Undation Model of van Bemmelen.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] This can act on various scales, from the small scale of one island arc up to the larger scale of an entire ocean basin.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Alfred Wegener, being a meteorologist, had proposed tidal forces and centrifugal forces as the main driving mechanisms behind continental drift; however, these forces were considered far too small to cause continental motion as the concept was of continents plowing through oceanic crust.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Therefore, Wegener later changed his position and asserted that convection currents are the main driving force of plate tectonics in the last edition of his book in 1929.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Global deformation of the geoid due to small displacements of the rotational pole with respect to Earth's crust.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Other smaller deformation effects of the crust due to wobbles and spin movements of Earth's rotation on a smaller timescale.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The centrifugal force, which is treated as a slight modification of gravity.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] For these mechanisms to be overall valid, systematic relationships should exist all over the globe between the orientation and kinematics of deformation and the geographical latitudinal and longitudinal grid of Earth itself.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Later studies (discussed below on this page), therefore, invoked many of the relationships recognized during this pre-plate tectonics period to support their theories (see reviews of these various mechanisms related to Earth rotation in the work of van Dijk and collaborators).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Of the many forces discussed above, tidal force is still highly debated and defended as a possible principal driving force of plate tectonics.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The other forces are only used in global geodynamic models not using plate tectonics concepts (therefore beyond the discussions treated in this section) or proposed as minor modulations within the overall plate tectonics model.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Bostrom presented evidence for a general westward drift of Earth's lithosphere with respect to the mantle, based on the steepness of the subduction zones (shallow dipping towards the east, steeply dipping towards the west).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] They concluded that tidal forces (the tidal lag or "friction") caused by Earth's rotation and the forces acting upon it by the Moon are a driving force for plate tectonics.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] As Earth spins eastward beneath the Moon, the Moon's gravity ever so slightly pulls Earth's surface layer back westward, just as proposed by Alfred Wegener (see above).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] Since 1990 this theory has been mainly advocated by Doglioni and co-workers (Doglioni 1990), such as in a more recent 2006 study, where scientists reviewed and advocated these ideas.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] It has been suggested in Lovett (2006) that this observation may also explain why Venus and Mars have no plate tectonics, as Venus has no moon and Mars' moons are too small to have significant tidal effects on the planet.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] In the same paper the authors admit, however, that relative to the lower mantle, there is a slight westward component in the motions of all the plates.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] They demonstrated though that the westward drift, seen only for the past 30 Ma, is attributed to the increased dominance of the steadily growing and accelerating Pacific plate.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The debate is still open, and a 2022 paper by Hofmeister et al. revived the idea of the interaction between Earth's rotation and the Moon as the main driving force for plate movement.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The role of water has been proposed to be crucial in plate tectonics on Earth.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The vector of a plate's motion is a function of all the forces acting on the plate; however, therein lies the problem regarding the degree to which each process contributes to the overall motion of each tectonic plate.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The diversity of geodynamic settings and the properties of each plate result from the impact of the various processes actively driving each individual plate.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] One method of dealing with this problem is to consider the relative rate at which each plate is moving as well as the evidence related to the significance of each process to the overall driving force on the plate.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] One of the most significant correlations discovered to date is that lithospheric plates attached to downgoing (subducting) plates move much faster than other types of plates.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The Pacific plate, for instance, is essentially surrounded by zones of subduction (the so-called Ring of Fire) and moves much faster than the plates of the Atlantic basin, which are attached (perhaps one could say 'welded') to adjacent continents instead of subducting plates.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] It is thus thought that forces associated with the downgoing plate (slab pull and slab suction) are the driving forces which determine the motion of plates, except for those plates which are not being subducted.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p01] The driving forces of plate motion continue to be active subjects of on-going research within geophysics and tectonophysics.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The development of the theory of plate tectonics was the scientific and cultural change which occurred during a period of 50 years of scientific debate.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The event of the acceptance itself was a paradigm shift and can therefore be classified as a scientific revolution, now described as the Plate Tectonics Revolution.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Around the start of the twentieth century, various theorists unsuccessfully attempted to explain the many geographical, geological, and biological continuities between continents.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] In 1912, the meteorologist Alfred Wegener described what he called continental drift, an idea that culminated fifty years later in the modern theory of plate tectonics.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Wegener expanded his theory in his 1915 book *The Origin of Continents and Oceans*.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Starting from the idea (also expressed by his forerunners) that the present continents once formed a single land mass (later called Pangaea), Wegener suggested that these separated and drifted apart, likening them to "icebergs" of low density sial floating on a sea of denser sima.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Supporting evidence for the idea came from the dove-tailing outlines of South America's east coast and Africa's west coast Antonio Snider-Pellegrini had drawn on his maps, and from the matching of the rock formations along these edges.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Confirmation of their previous contiguous nature also came from the fossil plants *Glossopteris* and *Gangamopteris*, and the therapsid or mammal-like reptile *Lystrosaurus*, all widely distributed over South America, Africa, Antarctica, India, and Australia.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The evidence for such an erstwhile joining of these continents was patent to field geologists working in the southern hemisphere.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The South African Alex du Toit put together a mass of such information in his 1937 publication *Our Wandering Continents*, and went further than Wegener in recognising the strong links between the Gondwana fragments.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Wegener's work was initially not widely accepted, in part due to a lack of detailed evidence but mostly because of the lack of a reasonable physically supported mechanism.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Earth might have a solid crust and mantle and a liquid core, but there seemed to be no way that portions of the crust could move around.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Many distinguished scientists of the time, such as Harold Jeffreys and Charles Schuchert, were outspoken critics of continental drift.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Despite much opposition, the view of continental drift gained support and a lively debate started between "drifters" or "mobilists" (proponents of the theory) and "fixists" (opponents).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] During the 1920s, 1930s and 1940s, the former reached important milestones proposing that convection currents might have driven the plate movements, and that spreading may have occurred below the sea within the oceanic crust.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Concepts close to the elements of plate tectonics were proposed by geophysicists and geologists (both fixists and mobilists) like Vening-Meinesz, Holmes, and Umbgrove.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] In 1941, Otto Ampferer described, in his publication "Thoughts on the motion picture of the Atlantic region", processes that anticipated seafloor spreading and subduction.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] One of the first pieces of geophysical evidence that was used to support the movement of lithospheric plates came from paleomagnetism.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] This is based on the fact that rocks of different ages show a variable magnetic field direction, evidenced by studies since the mid–nineteenth century.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The magnetic north and south poles reverse through time, and, especially important in paleotectonic studies, the relative position of the magnetic north pole varies through time.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Initially, during the first half of the twentieth century, the latter phenomenon was explained by introducing what was called "polar wander" (see apparent polar wander) (i.e., it was assumed that the north pole location had been shifting through time).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] An alternative explanation, though, was that the continents had moved (shifted and rotated) relative to the north pole, and each continent, in fact, shows its own "polar wander path".
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] During the late 1950s, it was successfully shown on two occasions that these data could show the validity of continental drift: by Keith Runcorn in a paper in 1956, and by Warren Carey in a symposium held in March 1956.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] All this evidence, both from the ocean floor and from the continental margins, made it clear around 1965 that continental drift was feasible.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The theory of plate tectonics was defined in a series of papers between 1965 and 1967.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The theory revolutionized the Earth sciences, explaining a diverse range of geological phenomena and their implications in other studies such as paleogeography and paleobiology.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, geologists assumed that Earth's major features were fixed, and that most geologic features such as basin development and mountain ranges could be explained by vertical crustal movement, described in what is called the geosynclinal theory.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Generally, this was placed in the context of a contracting planet Earth due to heat loss in the course of a relatively short geological time.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] It was observed as early as 1596 that the opposite coasts of the Atlantic Ocean—or, more precisely, the edges of the continental shelves—have similar shapes and seem to have once fitted together.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Since that time many theories were proposed to explain this apparent complementarity, but the assumption of a solid Earth made these various proposals difficult to accept.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The discovery of radioactivity and its associated heating properties in 1895 prompted a re-examination of the apparent age of Earth.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] This had previously been estimated by its cooling rate under the assumption that Earth's surface radiated like a black body.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Those calculations had implied that, even if it started at red heat, Earth would have dropped to its present temperature in a few tens of millions of years.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Armed with the knowledge of a new heat source, scientists realized that Earth would be much older, and that its core was still sufficiently hot to be liquid.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] By 1915, after having published a first article in 1912, Alfred Wegener was making serious arguments for the idea of continental drift in the first edition of *The Origin of Continents and Oceans*.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] In that book (re-issued in four successive editions up to the final one in 1936), he noted how the east coast of South America and the west coast of Africa looked as if they were once attached.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Furthermore, when the rock strata of the margins of separate continents are very similar it suggests that these rocks were formed in the same way, implying that they were joined initially.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] For instance, parts of Scotland and Ireland contain rocks very similar to those found in Newfoundland and New Brunswick.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Furthermore, the Caledonian Mountains of Europe and parts of the Appalachian Mountains of North America are very similar in structure and lithology.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] However, his ideas were not taken seriously by many geologists, who pointed out that there was no apparent mechanism for continental drift.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Specifically, they did not see how continental rock could plow through the much denser rock that makes up oceanic crust.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Wegener could not explain the force that drove continental drift, and his vindication did not come until after his death in 1930.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] As it was observed early that although granite existed on continents, seafloor seemed to be composed of denser basalt, the prevailing concept during the first half of the twentieth century was that there were two types of crust, named "sial" (continental type crust) and "sima" (oceanic type crust).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Furthermore, it was supposed that a static shell of strata was present under the continents.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] It therefore looked apparent that a layer of basalt (sial) underlies the continental rocks.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] However, based on abnormalities in plumb line deflection by the Andes in Peru, Pierre Bouguer had deduced that less-dense mountains must have a downward projection into the denser layer underneath.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The concept that mountains had "roots" was confirmed by George B.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Airy a hundred years later, during study of Himalayan gravitation, and seismic studies detected corresponding density variations.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Therefore, by the mid-1950s, the question remained unresolved as to whether mountain roots were clenched in surrounding basalt or were floating on it like an iceberg.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] During the 20th century, improvements in and greater use of seismic instruments such as seismographs enabled scientists to learn that earthquakes tend to be concentrated in specific areas, most notably along the oceanic trenches and spreading ridges.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] By the late 1920s, seismologists were beginning to identify several prominent earthquake zones parallel to the trenches that typically were inclined 40–60° from the horizontal and extended several hundred kilometers into Earth.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] These zones later became known as Wadati–Benioff zones, or simply Benioff zones, in honor of the seismologists who first recognized them, Kiyoo Wadati of Japan and Hugo Benioff of the United States.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The study of global seismicity greatly advanced in the 1960s with the establishment of the Worldwide Standardized Seismograph Network (WWSSN) to monitor the compliance of the 1963 treaty banning above-ground testing of nuclear weapons.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The much improved data from the WWSSN instruments allowed seismologists to map precisely the zones of earthquake concentration worldwide.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Meanwhile, debates developed around the phenomenon of polar wander.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Since the early debates of continental drift, scientists had discussed and used evidence that polar drift had occurred because continents seemed to have moved through different climatic zones during the past.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Furthermore, paleomagnetic data had shown that the magnetic pole had also shifted during time.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Reasoning in an opposite way, the continents might have shifted and rotated, while the pole remained relatively fixed.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] This was immediately followed by a symposium on continental drift in Tasmania in March 1956 organised by S.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Warren Carey who had been one of the supporters and promotors of Continental Drift since the thirties During this symposium, some of the participants used the evidence in the theory of an expansion of the global crust, a theory which had been proposed by other workers decades earlier.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] In this hypothesis, the shifting of the continents is explained by a large increase in the size of Earth since its formation.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] However, although the theory still has supporters in science, this is generally regarded as unsatisfactory because there is no convincing mechanism to produce a significant expansion of Earth.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Other work during the following years would soon show that the evidence was equally in support of continental drift on a globe with a stable radius.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] During the 1930s up to the late 1950s, works by Vening-Meinesz, Holmes, Umbgrove, and numerous others outlined concepts that were close or nearly identical to modern plate tectonics theory.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] In particular, the English geologist Arthur Holmes proposed in 1920 that plate junctions might lie beneath the sea, and in 1928 that convection currents within the mantle might be the driving force.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] They also found that the oceanic crust was much thinner than continental crust.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] All these new findings raised important and intriguing questions.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The new data that had been collected on the ocean basins also showed particular characteristics regarding the bathymetry.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] One of the major outcomes of these datasets was that all along the globe, a system of mid-oceanic ridges was detected.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] An important conclusion was that along this system, new ocean floor was being created, which led to the concept of the "Great Global Rift".
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] This was described in the crucial paper of Bruce Heezen (1960) based on his work with Marie Tharp, which would trigger a real revolution in thinking.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] A profound consequence of seafloor spreading is that new crust was, and still is, being continually created along the oceanic ridges.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] For this reason, Heezen initially advocated the so-called "expanding Earth" hypothesis of S.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Therefore, the question remained as to how new crust could continuously be added along the oceanic ridges without increasing the size of Earth.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] In reality, this question had been solved already by numerous scientists during the 1940s and the 1950s, like Arthur Holmes, Vening-Meinesz, Coates and many others: The crust in excess disappeared along what were called the oceanic trenches, where so-called "subduction" occurred.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Therefore, when various scientists during the early 1960s started to reason on the data at their disposal regarding the ocean floor, the pieces of the theory quickly fell into place.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The question particularly intrigued Harry Hammond Hess, a Princeton University geologist and a Naval Reserve Rear Admiral, and Robert S.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Dietz, a scientist with the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey who coined the term *seafloor spreading*.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Geological Survey described the main features of island arc subduction in the Aleutian Islands.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] His paper, though little noted (and sometimes even ridiculed) at the time, has since been called "seminal" and "prescient".
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] In reality, it shows that the work by the European scientists on island arcs and mountain belts performed and published during the 1930s up until the 1950s was applied and appreciated also in the United States.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] If Earth's crust was expanding along the oceanic ridges, Hess and Dietz reasoned like Holmes and others before them, it must be shrinking elsewhere.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Hess followed Heezen, suggesting that new oceanic crust continuously spreads away from the ridges in a conveyor belt–like motion.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] And, using the mobilistic concepts developed before, he correctly concluded that many millions of years later, the oceanic crust eventually descends along the continental margins where oceanic trenches—very deep, narrow canyons—are formed, e.g. along the rim of the Pacific Ocean basin.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The important step Hess made was that convection currents would be the driving force in this process, arriving at the same conclusions as Holmes had decades before with the only difference that the thinning of the ocean crust was performed using Heezen's mechanism of spreading along the ridges.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Hess therefore concluded that the Atlantic Ocean was expanding while the Pacific Ocean was shrinking.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] In effect, the ocean basins are perpetually being "recycled", with the forming of new crust and the destruction of old oceanic lithosphere occurring simultaneously.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Thus, the new mobilistic concepts neatly explained why Earth does not get bigger with sea floor spreading, why there is so little sediment accumulation on the ocean floor, and why oceanic rocks are much younger than continental rocks.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Beginning in the 1950s, scientists like Victor Vacquier, using magnetic instruments (magnetometers) adapted from airborne devices developed during World War II to detect submarines, began recognizing odd magnetic variations across the ocean floor.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] This finding, though unexpected, was not entirely surprising because it was known that basalt—the iron-rich, volcanic rock making up the ocean floor—contains a strongly magnetic mineral (magnetite) and can locally distort compass readings.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] This distortion was recognized by Icelandic mariners as early as the late 18th century.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] More importantly, because the presence of magnetite gives the basalt measurable magnetic properties, these newly discovered magnetic variations provided another means to study the deep ocean floor.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] When newly formed rock cools, such magnetic materials recorded Earth's magnetic field at the time.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] As more and more of the seafloor was mapped during the 1950s, the magnetic variations turned out not to be random or isolated occurrences, but instead revealed recognizable patterns.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] When these magnetic patterns were mapped over a wide region, the ocean floor showed a zebra-like pattern: one stripe with normal polarity and the adjoining stripe with reversed polarity.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The overall pattern, defined by these alternating bands of normally and reversely polarized rock, became known as magnetic striping, and was published by Ron G.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Mason and co-workers in 1961, who did not find, though, an explanation for these data in terms of sea floor spreading, like Vine, Matthews and Morley a few years later.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The discovery of magnetic striping called for an explanation.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] In the early 1960s scientists such as Heezen, Hess and Dietz had begun to theorise that mid-ocean ridges mark structurally weak zones where the ocean floor was being ripped in two lengthwise along the ridge crest (see the previous paragraph).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] New magma from deep within Earth rises easily through these weak zones and eventually erupts along the crest of the ridges to create new oceanic crust.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] This process, at first denominated the "conveyer belt hypothesis" and later called seafloor spreading, operating over many millions of years continues to form new ocean floor all across the 50,000 km-long system of mid-ocean ridges.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Only four years after the maps with the "zebra pattern" of magnetic stripes were published, the link between sea floor spreading and these patterns was recognized independently by Lawrence Morley, and by Fred Vine and Drummond Matthews, in 1963, (the Vine–Matthews–Morley hypothesis).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] 3. stripes of rock parallel to the ridge crest alternate in magnetic polarity (normal-reversed-normal, etc.), suggesting that they were formed during different epochs documenting the (already known from independent studies) normal and reversal episodes of Earth's magnetic field.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] By explaining both the zebra-like magnetic striping and the construction of the mid-ocean ridge system, the seafloor spreading hypothesis (SFS) quickly gained converts and represented another major advance in the development of the plate-tectonics theory.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Furthermore, the oceanic crust came to be appreciated as a natural "tape recording" of the history of the geomagnetic field reversals (GMFR) of Earth's magnetic field.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] According to a hypothesis proposed by Robert Stern and Taras Gerya, plate tectonics are a necessary criterion for a planet to be able to sustain complex life because of the role plate tectonics plays in regulating the carbon cycle.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Continental drift theory helps biogeographers to explain the disjunct biogeographic distribution of present-day life found on different continents but having similar ancestors.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Reconstruction is used to establish past (and future) plate configurations, helping determine the shape and make-up of ancient supercontinents and providing a basis for paleogeography.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Active plate boundaries are defined by their seismicity.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Past plate boundaries within existing plates are identified from a variety of evidence, such as the presence of ophiolites that are indicative of vanished oceans.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The timing of the emergence of plate tectonics on Earth has been the subject of considerable controversy, with the estimated time varying wildly between researchers, spanning 85% of Earth's history.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The increasingly felsic nature of preserved rocks between 3 and 2.5 billion years ago implies that subduction zones had emerged by this time, with preserved zircons suggesting that subduction may have begun as early as 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Early subduction zones appear to have been temporary and localized, though to what degree is controversial.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Other authors have suggested that plate tectonics were already functional in the Hadean, over 4 billion years ago.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Various types of quantitative and semi-quantitative information are available to constrain past plate motions.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The geometric fit between continents, such as between west Africa and South America is still an important part of plate reconstruction.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Magnetic stripe patterns provide a reliable guide to relative plate motions going back into the Jurassic period.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The tracks of hotspots give absolute reconstructions, but these are only available back to the Cretaceous.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Older reconstructions rely mainly on paleomagnetic pole data, although these only constrain the latitude and rotation, but not the longitude.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Combining poles of different ages in a particular plate to produce apparent polar wander paths provides a method for comparing the motions of different plates through time.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Additional evidence comes from the distribution of certain sedimentary rock types, faunal provinces shown by particular fossil groups, and the position of orogenic belts.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The movement of plates has caused the formation and break-up of continents over time, including occasional formation of a supercontinent that contains most or all of the continents.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The supercontinent Columbia or Nuna formed during a period of 2,000 to 1,800 million years ago and broke up about 1,500 to 1,300 million years ago.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The supercontinent Rodinia is thought to have formed about 1 billion years ago and to have embodied most or all of Earth's continents, and broken up into eight continents around 600 million years ago.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The eight continents later re-assembled into another supercontinent called Pangaea; Pangaea broke up into Laurasia (which became North America and Eurasia) and Gondwana (which became the remaining continents).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The Himalayas, the world's tallest mountain range, are assumed to have been formed by the collision of two major plates.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Before uplift, the area where they stand was covered by the Tethys Ocean.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Depending on how they are defined, there are usually seven or eight "major" plates: African, Antarctic, Eurasian, North American, South American, Pacific, and Indo-Australian.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The latter is sometimes subdivided into the Indian and Australian plates.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] There are dozens of smaller plates, the eight largest of which are the Arabian, Caribbean, Juan de Fuca, Cocos, Nazca, Philippine Sea, Scotia and Somali.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] During the 2020s, new proposals have come forward that divide Earth's crust into many smaller plates, called terranes, which reflects the fact that Plate reconstructions show that the larger plates have been internally deformed and oceanic and continental plates have been fragmented over time.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] This has resulted in the definition of roughly 1200 terranes inside the oceanic plates, continental blocks and the mobile zones (mountainous belts) that separate them.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The motion of the tectonic plates is determined by remote sensing satellite data sets, calibrated with ground station measurements.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The appearance of plate tectonics on terrestrial planets is related to planetary mass, with more massive planets than Earth expected to exhibit plate tectonics.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Earth may be a borderline case, owing its tectonic activity to abundant water (silica and water form a deep eutectic).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Venus shows no evidence of active plate tectonics.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] However, the numerous well-preserved impact craters have been used as a dating method to approximately date the Venusian surface (since there are thus far no known samples of Venusian rock to be dated by more reliable methods).
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Dates derived are dominantly in the range 500 to 750 million years ago, although ages of up to 1,200 million years ago have been calculated.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] This research has led to the fairly well accepted hypothesis that Venus has undergone an essentially complete volcanic resurfacing at least once in its distant past, with the last event taking place approximately within the range of estimated surface ages.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] While the mechanism of such an impressive thermal event remains a debated issue in Venusian geosciences, some scientists are advocates of processes involving plate motion to some extent.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] One explanation for Venus's lack of plate tectonics is that on Venus temperatures are too high for significant water to be present.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Earth's crust is soaked with water, and water plays an important role in the development of shear zones.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Plate tectonics requires weak surfaces in the crust along which crustal slices can move, and it may well be that such weakening never took place on Venus because of the absence of water.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] However, some researchers remain convinced that plate tectonics is or was once active on this planet.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Mars is considerably smaller than Earth and Venus, and there is evidence for ice on its surface and in its crust.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] In the 1990s, it was proposed that Martian Crustal Dichotomy was created by plate tectonic processes.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Scientists have since determined that it was created either by upwelling within the Martian mantle that thickened the crust of the Southern Highlands and formed Tharsis or by a giant impact that excavated the Northern Lowlands.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Valles Marineris may be a tectonic boundary.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Observations made of the magnetic field of Mars by the *Mars Global Surveyor* spacecraft in 1999 showed patterns of magnetic striping discovered on this planet.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Some scientists interpreted these as requiring plate tectonic processes, such as seafloor spreading.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] However, their data failed a "magnetic reversal test", which is used to see if they were formed by flipping polarities of a global magnetic field.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Some of the satellites of Jupiter have features that may be related to plate-tectonic style deformation, although the materials and specific mechanisms may be different from plate-tectonic activity on Earth.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] On 8 September 2014, NASA reported finding evidence of plate tectonics on Europa, a satellite of Jupiter—the first sign of subduction activity on another world other than Earth.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Titan, the largest moon of Saturn, was reported to show tectonic activity in images taken by the *Huygens* probe, which landed on Titan on January 14, 2005.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] The mechanisms of plate tectonics on icy moons, particularly Earth-like plate tectonics are not widely agreed upon or well understood.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Plate tectonics on Earth is hypothesized to be driven by “slab pull,” where the sinking of the more dense subducting plate provides the spreading force for mid-ocean ridges. “Ridge push” is comparatively weak in Earth's plate tectonics.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Extensional features are abundant on icy moons, but compressional features are sparse.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Furthermore, subducting less dense ice into a more dense fluid is difficult to explain.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Force balance modeling suggests that subduction is likely to create large scale topographic forcing across icy moons, because the buoyant force is orders of magnitude greater than subducting forces.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Fracturing and plate-like motion is more easily explained by volume changes and ice-shell motion that is decoupled from interior motion.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] On Earth-sized planets, plate tectonics is more likely if there are oceans of water.
[src:geophysics/plate-tectonics-p02] Consideration of plate tectonics is a part of the search for extraterrestrial intelligence and extraterrestrial life.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] A **seismic wave** is a mechanical wave of acoustic energy that travels through the Earth or another planetary body.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] It can result from an earthquake (or generally, a quake), volcanic eruption, magma movement, a large landslide, and a large man-made explosion that produces low-frequency acoustic energy.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Seismic waves are studied by seismologists, who record the waves using seismometers, hydrophones (in water), or accelerometers.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Seismic waves are distinguished from seismic noise (ambient vibration), which is persistent low-amplitude vibration arising from a variety of natural and anthropogenic sources.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] The propagation velocity of a seismic wave depends on the density and elasticity of the medium as well as the type of wave.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Velocity tends to increase with depth through Earth's crust and mantle, but drops sharply going from the mantle to Earth's outer core.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Earthquakes create distinct types of waves with different velocities.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] When recorded by a seismic observatory, their different travel times help scientists locate the quake's hypocenter.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] In geophysics, the refraction or reflection of seismic waves is used for research into Earth's internal structure.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Scientists sometimes generate and measure vibrations to investigate shallow, subsurface structure.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Among the many types of seismic waves, one can make a broad distinction between *body waves*, which travel through the Earth, and *surface waves*, which travel at the Earth's surface.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Other modes of wave propagation exist than those described in this article; though of comparatively minor importance for earth-borne waves, they are important in the case of asteroseismology.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Body waves travel through the interior of the Earth along paths controlled by the material properties in terms of density and modulus (stiffness).
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] The density and modulus, in turn, vary according to temperature, composition, and material phase.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] This effect resembles the refraction of light waves.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Two types of particle motion result in two types of body waves: ***Primary*** and ***Secondary*** waves.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] This distinction was recognized in 1830 by the French mathematician Siméon Denis Poisson.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Primary waves (P waves) are compressional waves that are longitudinal in nature.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] P waves are pressure waves that travel faster than other waves through the earth to arrive at seismograph stations first, hence the name "Primary".
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] These waves can travel through any type of material, including fluids, and can travel nearly 1.7 times faster than the S waves.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] In air, they take the form of sound waves, hence they travel at the speed of sound.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Typical speeds are 330 m/s in air, 1450 m/s in water and about 5000 m/s in granite.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Secondary waves (S waves) are shear waves that are transverse in nature.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Following an earthquake event, S waves arrive at seismograph stations after the faster-moving P waves and displace the ground perpendicular to the direction of propagation.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Depending on the propagational direction, the wave can take on different surface characteristics; for example, in the case of horizontally polarized S waves, the ground moves alternately to one side and then the other.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] S waves can travel only through solids, as fluids (liquids and gases) do not support shear stresses.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] S waves are slower than P waves, and speeds are typically around 60% of that of P waves in any given material.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Shear waves can not travel through any liquid medium, so the absence of S waves in earth's outer core suggests a liquid state.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Seismic surface waves travel along the Earth's surface.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] They can be classified as a form of mechanical surface wave.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Surface waves diminish in amplitude as they get farther from the surface and propagate more slowly than seismic body waves (P and S).
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Surface waves from very large earthquakes can have globally observable amplitude of several centimeters.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] The existence of these waves was predicted by John William Strutt, Lord Rayleigh, in 1885.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] They are slower than body waves, e.g., at roughly 90% of the velocity of S waves for typical homogeneous elastic media.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] In a layered medium (e.g., the crust and upper mantle) the velocity of the Rayleigh waves depends on their frequency and wavelength.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Love waves are horizontally polarized shear waves (SH waves), existing only in the presence of a layered medium.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] They are named after Augustus Edward Hough Love, a British mathematician who created a mathematical model of the waves in 1911.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] They usually travel slightly faster than Rayleigh waves, about 90% of the S wave velocity.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] A Stoneley wave is a type of boundary wave (or interface wave) that propagates along a solid-fluid boundary or, under specific conditions, also along a solid-solid boundary.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Amplitudes of Stoneley waves have their maximum values at the boundary between the two contacting media and decay exponentially away from the contact.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] These waves can also be generated along the walls of a fluid-filled borehole, being an important source of coherent noise in vertical seismic profiles (VSP) and making up the low frequency component of the source in sonic logging.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] The equation for Stoneley waves was first given by Dr.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Robert Stoneley (1894–1976), emeritus professor of seismology, Cambridge.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Free oscillations of the Earth are standing waves, the result of interference between two surface waves traveling in opposite directions.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Interference of Rayleigh waves results in *spheroidal oscillation S* while interference of Love waves gives *toroidal oscillation T*.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] The modes of oscillations are specified by three numbers, e.g., nSlm, where *l* is the angular order number (or *spherical harmonic degree*, see Spherical harmonics for more details).
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] The number *m* is the azimuthal order number.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] It may take on 2*l*+1 values from −*l* to +*l*.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] The number *n* is the *radial order number*.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] It means the wave with *n* zero crossings in radius.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] For spherically symmetric Earth the period for given *n* and *l* does not depend on *m*.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Some examples of spheroidal oscillations are the "breathing" mode 0S0, which involves an expansion and contraction of the whole Earth, and has a period of about 20 minutes; and the "rugby" mode 0S2, which involves expansions along two alternating directions, and has a period of about 54 minutes.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] The mode 0S1 does not exist because it would require a change in the center of gravity, which would require an external force.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Of the fundamental toroidal modes, 0T1 represents changes in Earth's rotation rate; although this occurs, it is much too slow to be useful in seismology.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] The mode 0T2 describes a twisting of the northern and southern hemispheres relative to each other; it has a period of about 44 minutes.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] The first observations of free oscillations of the Earth were done during the great 1960 earthquake in Chile.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Presently the periods of thousands of modes have been observed.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] These data are used for constraining large scale structures of the Earth's interior.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] When an earthquake occurs, seismographs near the epicenter are able to record both P and S waves, but those at a greater distance no longer detect the high frequencies of the first S wave.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Since shear waves cannot pass through liquids, this phenomenon was original evidence for the now well-established observation that the Earth has a liquid outer core, as demonstrated by Richard Dixon Oldham.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] This kind of observation has also been used to argue, by seismic testing, that the Moon has a solid core, although recent geodetic studies suggest the core is still molten.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] The path that a wave takes between the focus and the observation point is often drawn as a ray diagram.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Each path is denoted by a set of letters that describe the trajectory and phase through the Earth.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] In general, an upper case denotes a transmitted wave and a lower case denotes a reflected wave.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] In the case of local or nearby earthquakes, the difference in the arrival times of the P and S waves can be used to determine the distance to the event.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] In the case of earthquakes that have occurred at global distances, three or more geographically diverse observing stations (using a common clock) recording P wave arrivals permits the computation of a unique time and location on the planet for the event.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Typically, dozens or even hundreds of P wave arrivals are used to calculate hypocenters.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] The misfit generated by a hypocenter calculation is known as "the residual".
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Residuals of 0.5 second or less are typical for distant events, residuals of 0.1–0.2 s typical for local events, meaning most reported P arrivals fit the computed hypocenter that well.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Typically a location program will start by assuming the event occurred at a depth of about 33 km; then it minimizes the residual by adjusting depth.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Most events occur at depths shallower than about 40 km, but some occur as deep as 700 km.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] A quick way to determine the distance from a location to the origin of a seismic wave less than 200 km away is to take the difference in arrival time of the P wave and the S wave in seconds and multiply by 8 kilometers per second.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Modern seismic arrays use more complicated earthquake location techniques.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] At teleseismic distances, the first arriving P waves have necessarily travelled deep into the mantle, and perhaps have even refracted into the outer core of the planet, before travelling back up to the Earth's surface where the seismographic stations are located.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] The waves travel more quickly than if they had traveled in a straight line from the earthquake.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] This is due to the appreciably increased velocities within the planet, and is termed Huygens' Principle.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Density in the planet increases with depth, which would slow the waves, but the modulus of the rock increases much more, so deeper means faster.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Therefore, a longer route can take a shorter time.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] The travel time must be calculated very accurately in order to compute a precise hypocenter.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Since P waves move at many kilometers per second, being off on travel-time calculation by even a half second can mean an error of many kilometers in terms of distance.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] In practice, P arrivals from many stations are used and the errors cancel out, so the computed epicenter is likely to be quite accurate, on the order of 10–50 km or so around the world.
[src:geophysics/seismic-wave] Dense arrays of nearby sensors such as those that exist in California can provide accuracy of roughly a kilometer, and much greater accuracy is possible when timing is measured directly by cross-correlation of seismogram waveforms.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Paleoseismology is a related field that uses geology to infer information regarding past earthquakes.
[src:geophysics/seismology] A recording of Earth's motion as a function of time, created by a seismograph is called a seismogram.
[src:geophysics/seismology] A **seismologist** is a scientist who works in basic or applied seismology.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Scholarly interest in earthquakes can be traced back to antiquity.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Early speculations on the natural causes of earthquakes were included in the writings of Thales of Miletus (c.
[src:geophysics/seismology] In 132 CE, Zhang Heng of China's Han dynasty designed the first known seismoscope.
[src:geophysics/seismology] In the 17th century, Athanasius Kircher argued that earthquakes were caused by the movement of fire within a system of channels inside the Earth.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Martin Lister (1638–1712) and Nicolas Lemery (1645–1715) proposed that earthquakes were caused by chemical explosions within the Earth.
[src:geophysics/seismology] The Lisbon earthquake of 1755, coinciding with the general flowering of science in Europe, set in motion intensified scientific attempts to understand the behaviour and causation of earthquakes.
[src:geophysics/seismology] The earliest responses include work by John Bevis (1757) and John Michell (1761).
[src:geophysics/seismology] Michell determined that earthquakes originate within the Earth and were waves of movement caused by "shifting masses of rock miles below the surface".
[src:geophysics/seismology] In response to a series of earthquakes near Comrie in Scotland in 1839, a committee was formed in the United Kingdom in order to produce better detection methods for earthquakes.
[src:geophysics/seismology] The outcome of this was the production of one of the first modern seismometers by James David Forbes, first presented in a report by David Milne-Home in 1842.
[src:geophysics/seismology] This seismometer was an inverted pendulum, which recorded the measurements of seismic activity through the use of a pencil placed on paper above the pendulum.
[src:geophysics/seismology] The designs provided did not prove effective, according to Milne's reports.
[src:geophysics/seismology] From 1857, Robert Mallet laid the foundation of modern instrumental seismology and carried out seismological experiments using explosives.
[src:geophysics/seismology] He is also responsible for coining the word "seismology." He is widely considered to be the "Father of Seismology".
[src:geophysics/seismology] In 1889 Ernst von Rebeur-Paschwitz recorded the first teleseismic earthquake signal (an earthquake in Japan recorded at Pottsdam Germany).
[src:geophysics/seismology] In 1894 Fusakichi Omori demonstrated that the frequency of earthquake aftershocks decays following a mainshock, based on his analysis of the 1889 Kumamoto, 1891 Mino–Owari and the 1893 Kagoshima earthquakes.
[src:geophysics/seismology] In 1897, Emil Wiechert's theoretical calculations led him to conclude that the Earth's interior consists of a mantle of silicates, surrounding a core of iron.
[src:geophysics/seismology] In 1906 Richard Dixon Oldham identified the separate arrival of P waves, S waves and surface waves on seismograms and found the first clear evidence that the Earth has a central core.
[src:geophysics/seismology] In 1909, Andrija Mohorovičić, one of the founders of modern seismology, discovered and defined the Mohorovičić discontinuity.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Usually referred to as the "Moho discontinuity" or the "Moho," it is the boundary between the Earth's crust and the mantle.
[src:geophysics/seismology] It is defined by the distinct change in velocity of seismological waves as they pass through changing densities of rock.
[src:geophysics/seismology] In 1910, after studying the April 1906 San Francisco earthquake, Harry Fielding Reid put forward the "elastic rebound theory" which remains the foundation for modern tectonic studies.
[src:geophysics/seismology] The development of this theory depended on the considerable progress of earlier independent streams of work on the behavior of elastic materials and in mathematics.
[src:geophysics/seismology] An early scientific study of aftershocks from a destructive earthquake came after the January 1920 Xalapa earthquake.
[src:geophysics/seismology] An 80 kg (180 lb) Wiechert seismograph was brought to the Mexican city of Xalapa by rail after the earthquake.
[src:geophysics/seismology] The instrument was deployed to record its aftershocks.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Data from the seismograph would eventually determine that the mainshock was produced along a shallow crustal fault.
[src:geophysics/seismology] In 1926, Harold Jeffreys was the first to claim, based on his study of earthquake waves, that below the mantle, the core of the Earth is liquid.
[src:geophysics/seismology] In 1937, Inge Lehmann determined that within Earth's liquid outer core there is a solid inner core.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Longuet-Higgins elucidated the ocean processes responsible for the global background seismic microseism.
[src:geophysics/seismology] By the 1960s, Earth science had developed to the point where a comprehensive theory of the causation of seismic events and geodetic motions had come together in the now well-established theory of plate tectonics.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Seismic waves are elastic waves that propagate in solid or fluid materials.
[src:geophysics/seismology] They can be divided into *body waves* that travel through the interior of the materials; *surface waves* that travel along surfaces or interfaces between materials; and *normal modes*, a form of standing wave.
[src:geophysics/seismology] There are two types of body waves, pressure waves or primary waves (P waves) and shear or secondary waves (S waves).
[src:geophysics/seismology] P waves are longitudinal waves associated with compression and expansion, and involve particle motion parallel to the direction of wave propagation.
[src:geophysics/seismology] P waves are always the first waves to appear on a seismogram as they are the waves that travel fastest through solids.
[src:geophysics/seismology] S waves are transverse waves associated with shear, and involve particle motion perpendicular to the direction of wave propagation.
[src:geophysics/seismology] S waves travel more slowly than P waves so they appear later than P waves on a seismogram.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Because of their low shear strength, fluids cannot support transverse elastic waves, so S waves travel only in solids.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Surface waves are the result of P and S waves interacting with the surface of the Earth.
[src:geophysics/seismology] These waves are dispersive, meaning that different frequencies have different velocities.
[src:geophysics/seismology] The two main surface wave types are Rayleigh waves, which have both compressional and shear motions, and Love waves, which are purely shear.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Rayleigh waves result from the interaction of P waves and vertically polarized S waves with the surface and can exist in any solid medium.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Love waves are formed by horizontally polarized S waves interacting with the surface, and can only exist if there is a change in the elastic properties with depth in a solid medium, which is always the case in seismological applications.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Surface waves travel more slowly than P waves and S waves because they are the result of these waves traveling along indirect paths to interact with Earth's surface.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Because they travel along the surface of the Earth, their energy decays less rapidly than body waves (1/distance2 vs.
[src:geophysics/seismology] 1/distance3), and thus the shaking caused by surface waves is generally stronger than that of body waves, and the primary surface waves are often thus the largest signals on earthquake seismograms.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Surface waves are strongly excited when their source is close to the surface, as in a shallow earthquake or a near-surface explosion, and are much weaker for deep earthquake sources.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Both body and surface waves are traveling waves; however, large earthquakes can also make the entire Earth "ring" like a resonant bell.
[src:geophysics/seismology] This ringing is a mixture of normal modes with discrete frequencies and periods of approximately an hour or shorter.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Normal-mode motion caused by a very large earthquake can be observed for up to a month after the event.
[src:geophysics/seismology] The first observations of normal modes were made in the 1960s as the advent of higher-fidelity instruments coincided with two of the largest earthquakes of the 20th century, the 1960 Valdivia earthquake and the 1964 Alaska earthquake.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Since then, the normal modes of the Earth have given us some of the strongest constraints on the deep structure of the Earth.
[src:geophysics/seismology] One of the first attempts at the scientific study of earthquakes followed the 1755 Lisbon earthquake.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Other earthquakes that spurred major advancements in the science of seismology include the 1857 Basilicata earthquake, the 1906 San Francisco earthquake, the 1964 Alaska earthquake, the 2004 Sumatra-Andaman earthquake, and the 2011 Great East Japan earthquake.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Seismic waves produced by explosions or vibrating controlled sources are one of the primary methods of underground exploration in geophysics (in addition to many different electromagnetic methods such as induced polarization and magnetotellurics).
[src:geophysics/seismology] Controlled-source seismology has been used to map salt domes, anticlines and other geologic traps in petroleum-bearing rocks, faults, rock types, and long-buried giant meteor craters.
[src:geophysics/seismology] For example, the Chicxulub Crater, which was caused by an impact that has been implicated in the extinction of the dinosaurs, was localized to Central America by analyzing ejecta in the Cretaceous–Paleogene boundary, and then physically proven to exist using seismic maps from oil exploration.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Seismometers are sensors that detect and record the motion of the Earth arising from elastic waves.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Seismometers may be deployed at the Earth's surface, in shallow vaults, in boreholes, or underwater.
[src:geophysics/seismology] A complete instrument package that records seismic signals is called a seismograph.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Networks of seismographs continuously record ground motions around the world to facilitate the monitoring and analysis of global earthquakes and other sources of seismic activity.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Locating an earthquake's epicenter is done by trilateration with at least three seismometers.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Rapid location of earthquakes makes tsunami warnings possible because seismic waves travel considerably faster than tsunami waves.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Above-ocean meteor strikes with energies as high as 4.2 × 1013 J (equivalent to that released by an explosion of ten kilotons of TNT) have been recorded by seismographs, as have a number of industrial accidents and terrorist bombs and events (a field of study referred to as forensic seismology).
[src:geophysics/seismology] A major long-term motivation for the global seismographic monitoring has been for the detection and study of nuclear testing.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Because seismic waves commonly propagate efficiently as they interact with the internal structure of the Earth, they provide high-resolution noninvasive methods for studying the planet's interior.
[src:geophysics/seismology] One of the earliest important discoveries (suggested by Richard Dixon Oldham in 1906 and definitively shown by Harold Jeffreys in 1926) was that the outer core of the earth is liquid.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Since S waves do not pass through liquids, the liquid core causes a "shadow" on the side of the planet opposite the earthquake where no direct S waves are observed.
[src:geophysics/seismology] In addition, P waves travel much slower through the outer core than the mantle.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Processing readings from many seismometers using seismic tomography, seismologists have mapped the mantle of the earth to a resolution of several hundred kilometers.
[src:geophysics/seismology] This has enabled scientists to identify convection cells and other large-scale features such as the large low-shear-velocity provinces near the core–mantle boundary.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Public controversy over earthquake prediction erupted after Italian authorities indicted six seismologists and one government official for manslaughter in connection with a magnitude 6.3 earthquake in L'Aquila, Italy on April 5, 2009.
[src:geophysics/seismology] A report in Nature stated that the indictment was widely seen in Italy and abroad as being for failing to predict the earthquake and drew condemnation from the American Association for the Advancement of Science and the American Geophysical Union.
[src:geophysics/seismology] However, the magazine also indicated that the population of Aquila do not consider the failure to predict the earthquake to be the reason for the indictment, but rather the alleged failure of the scientists to evaluate and communicate risk.
[src:geophysics/seismology] The indictment claims that, at a special meeting in L'Aquila the week before the earthquake occurred, scientists and officials were more interested in pacifying the population than providing adequate information about earthquake risk and preparedness.
[src:geophysics/seismology] In locations where a historical record exists it may be used to estimate the timing, location and magnitude of future seismic events.
[src:geophysics/seismology] There are several interpretative factors to consider.
[src:geophysics/seismology] The epicentres or foci and magnitudes of historical earthquakes are subject to interpretation meaning it is possible that 5–6 Mw earthquakes described in the historical record could be larger events occurring elsewhere that were felt moderately in the populated areas that produced written records.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Documentation in the historic period may be sparse or incomplete, and not give a full picture of the geographic scope of an earthquake, or the historical record may only have earthquake records spanning a few centuries, a very short time frame in a seismic cycle.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Engineering seismology is the study and application of seismology for engineering purposes.
[src:geophysics/seismology] It generally applied to the branch of seismology that deals with the assessment of the seismic hazard of a site or region for the purposes of earthquake engineering.
[src:geophysics/seismology] It is, therefore, a link between earth science and civil engineering.
[src:geophysics/seismology] There are two principal components of engineering seismology.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Firstly, studying earthquake history (e.g. historical and instrumental catalogs of seismicity) and tectonics to assess the earthquakes that could occur in a region and their characteristics and frequency of occurrence.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Secondly, studying strong ground motions generated by earthquakes to assess the expected shaking from future earthquakes with similar characteristics.
[src:geophysics/seismology] These strong ground motions could either be observations from accelerometers or seismometers or those simulated by computers using various techniques, which are then often used to develop ground-motion prediction equations (or ground-motion models)[1] Archived 2023-06-09 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:geophysics/seismology] Seismological instruments can generate large amounts of data.
